FT  06 APR 93 / Mesnage appears in Guernsey court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michel Mesnage, a French trawler skipper, appeared in a Guernsey court
yesterday, Jimmy Burns writes. He was charged with fishing illegally in
British territorial waters off the island and with failing to comply with an
order from a fisheries protection officer.
Mr Mesnage faces a maximum Pounds 50,000 fine for the first offence and a
maximum Pounds 1,000 for the second. The charges relate to alleged incidents
10 days ago involving French fishing vessels and the Royal Navy. The case
was further adjourned until today.
Earlier yesterday more than a dozen British fishing vessels landed their
catches at the French port of Cherbourg without the feared protest action by
French fishermen. Last Friday French fishermen warned their British
counterparts not to go to French ports because of tensions over disputed
fishing rights and the arrest of Mr Mesnage.
