<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Patten vows to improve skills base
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTRODUCTION of vocational education for 16-to-19-year-olds in full-time
education is to be speeded up in the drive to improve the country's skill
base, Mr John Patten, the education secretary, said yesterday.
Mr Patten, who has given a much higher public profile to vocational
qualifications in recent weeks, told the Institute of Directors he would
like to see vocational qualifications developing into mainstream
qualifications, catering for up to half the age group.
Ambitious goals were essential if the UK was to meet the national targets
for achievement of vocational and educational qualifications set by the
Confederation of British Industry.
Mr Patten said that a number of alternative qualification routes were needed
in order to meet the national targets.
He stressed his commitment to retaining 'all that was best in the A-level
system' but said a central objective was to provide people with an
attractive vocational alternative. The new National Vocational
Qualifications (NVQs) and General National Vocational Qualifications (GNVQs)
for England, Wales and Northern Ireland were designed to do this.
The first GNVQs - in art and design, business, health and social care,
leisure and tourism and manufacturing - are being piloted in about 100
colleges and schools.
Mr Patten said he wanted GNVQs in at least two subjects to be available in
at least 1,500 schools and colleges by 1996. Pupils could take GNVQs
alongside GCSEs and A-levels.
'Vocational education has in the past been held in low esteem,' said Mr
Patten. 'We need to attack ingrained cultural attitudes that regard
practical and applied studies as inferior to theoretical A-level courses. We
need to promote parity of esteem between vocational and academic
qualifications.'
Mr Patten said employers had an important part to play and he hoped they
would all ensure that recruitment decisions and advertising material gave
due credit to GNVQ achievement.
Young people, he said, were sophisticated and could read signals from the
employment market. 'If they think that employers value higher levels of
education and skills, and are prepared to reward them, they will aim for
those higher levels. If they think that employers value the vocational
routes they will follow these routes.'
The Institute of Personnel Management has questioned whether numerical
targets for education and vocational qualifications will be adequate to
generate the skills needed to sustain the UK as an economic force in the
21st century.
Mr David Wright, vice-president of the institute, which has welcomed the
targets in principle, said in Personnel Management, the monthly magazine,
that there needed to be a more strategic approach to the types of skills
required.
He said: 'Relying on local labour market intelligence to match immediate
local demand for and supply of skills is fine, but there needs to be a more
strategic national and long-term focus.' It was to be regretted that such a
role was outside the remit of the new employer-led advisory body on the
targets.
A central role of the new body, the National Advisory Council for Education
and Training Targets, is to persuade employers in England and Wales to take
up national vocational qualifications.
Mr Wright said NVQs would not be welcomed by employers if they were
perceived to increase the price of training over and above present
expenditure and if they added to bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
