<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Consumer credit demand slips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEMAND FOR credit by consumers slackened in February, but remained above the
depressed levels of last year, government figures released yesterday show.
New borrowing through finance houses, building societies and certain bank
credit cards rose a seasonally adjusted Pounds 49m in February, after a
Pounds 151m rise in January.
Extra borrowings - taking into account repayments and excluding mortgages
and bank overdrafts - in the three months to the end of February totalled
Pounds 305m, well above the Pounds 64m in the previous three months.
The Central Statistical Office data reinforce recent indications of a muted
recovery. This interpretation was supported by Bank of England figures on
the M0 narrow measure of money supply and by the CSO's latest set of
cyclical economic indicators.
M0, which is mainly notes and coins in circulation, rose by a strong 4.9 per
cent in the year to March, compared with a 4.5 per cent year-on-year rise in
February.
The longer-leading index compiled by the CSO, which is supposed to give
advance warning of economic growth, registered 109.6 in February, after
108.9 in January.
In February consumers showed less willingness to use bank credit cards to
increase borrowings. They repaid a net Pounds 8m on cards which are part of
the Visa or Mastercard systems, after borrowing Pounds 40m on these cards in
January. In the three months to the end of February net repayments on cards
came to Pounds 11m, after repayments of Pounds 63m in the previous three
months.
Total new consumer credit in February taken through cards, building
societies and finance houses was Pounds 4.39bn, after Pounds 3.93bn in
January. Between December and February new credit came to Pounds 12.95bn, up
from Pounds 12.27bn in the previous three months.
The CSO published revised estimates of the amount of credit borrowed in the
last six months of last year that indicate demand for lending in the final
quarter was higher than previously thought.
Consumer loans through retailers, building societies, all types of credit
cards and other credit agencies rose by Pounds 291m in the final quarter
rather than the Pounds 153m initially estimated. The corresponding figure
for the third quarter was Pounds 203m, after a Pounds 392m first estimate.
Overseas institutions bought Pounds 1.031bn worth of gilts in February, the
biggest monthly figure since June 1991, figures from the Bank of England
show. Total gilt sales came to about Pounds 3.2bn in February.
</TEXT>
