<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Executive pay growth slows further
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL DIXON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXECUTIVES' pay rises slowed further over the 12 months to April 1,
according to the Noble Lowndes group of management consultants and
actuaries. But although employers are applying the brake, they are not
pushing it as hard as they were six months ago.
The group's index shows that the average pay for all ranks of executives
increased by 5.7 per cent in the 12 months ended last Thursday, compared
with 8.6 per cent in the 12 months to April 1 last year.
Of the latest 5.7-point gain, however, more than half has come in the six
months since September.
The index - which also includes the value of benefits such as cars and
pensions as well as salaries and bonuses - is based on a survey of 5,362
managers in 422 companies in the UK.
Noble Lowndes says that the proportion of managers whose pay is completely
frozen is now 6.3 per cent, compared with 7.1 per cent a year ago. The great
majority of the remainder have had rises of at least twice the government's
1.5 per cent ceiling on public-sector increases.
Among the managers, chief executives and directors of big companies with
sales turnovers of more than Pounds 600m have continued to improve their
differential over other groups.
Noble Lowndes, PO Box 144, Norfolk House, Wellesley Rd, Croydon CR9 3EB.
</TEXT>
