<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Annual-hours contracts spread rapidly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE USE OF contracts fixing the number of hours worked each year rather than
each week is increasing rapidly, particularly in the service sector, a
survey by the Institute of Personnel Management shows.
'Annualised hours' contracts allow companies to cope with varying demand and
cut overtime costs.
The survey, due to be published in full next month, found that of more than
80 organisations operating annualised hours schemes, 60 per cent had
introduced them since 1989. In the service sector, more than 65 per cent of
the companies surveyed had brought them in since 1991.
Nearly all the organisations using annualised hours were extremely
satisfied, the IPM said.
The majority also considered that employees liked it, although some workers
complained about 'reserve hours' in some schemes, which meant that they
could be called in to work at very short notice to cover absence or
unexpected demand.
Cardiff-based Matsushita Electric, making televisions and microwave ovens,
reported in the survey that it had saved about Pounds 3m since introducing
annualised hours for about 1,500 production workers in January last year.
The company has been able to organise working hours around seasonal
variations in demand - 60 per cent to 65 per cent of demand for its products
comes between September and December.
Some companies, however, including Bristol and West Building Society and
ITN, reported that the recession was making it difficult to decide on the
right number of hours one year ahead.
The institute reported that there was increasing evidence of annualised
hours contracts being introduced to retain valued staff, as well as for the
more traditional reasons of meeting demand and cutting overtime payments.
Some women returning to work after having children asked for annualised
hours so they could work more flexibly, it said.
</TEXT>
