<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Judges call eating-up time
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
RESTAURANTS ARE entitled to give customers 'eating-up time' in the same way
that public houses can give drinking-up time, the High Court ruled
yesterday.
In a decision that could have wide implications for the restaurant trade,
the judges ruled that magistrates erred in law in convicting Mr Anwar Amin,
joint holder of a licence for the Dhaka tandoori restaurant in Southampton,
of staying open too late.
The city's magistrates fined Mr Amin Pounds 100 in June 1991 when they found
him guilty of contravening a condition of his late-night refreshment house
licence which prevented him from 'keeping open' between 3am and 5am.
Mr Amin admitted that about 30 people were still eating at 3.45am on a
Sunday in November 1990, when two women police officers visited his Onslow
Road restaurant.
But he argued that the mere fact that the officers could get in through an
unlocked door did not necessarily mean the restaurant was being kept open
within the meaning of the Late Night Refreshment Houses Act 1969.
The act regulates places kept open between 10pm and 5am for 'public
refreshment, resort and entertainment'.
No customers were admitted after 3am, and diners were in various stages of
finishing their meals, Mr Amin argued.
Southampton magistrates decided he was guilty of an offence because the
officers could get into the restaurant without hindrance.
Allowing an appeal against the conviction, Mr Justice Rougier, sitting with
Lord Justice Watkins, said that if the magistrates' interpretation of the
law was correct it would place restaurant owners in 'an impossible
situation' and mean that customers had to be out by closing time. Those in
the restaurant at 3am were entitled to finish their meals, he said.
</TEXT>
