<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Joblessness 'will peak at 3.1m'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNEMPLOYMENT WILL continue to rise for only a few more months, peaking at
3.1m, but will still be about 2.5m by the end of the century, according to
the annual review of the economy and employment by the Institute for
Employment Research.
The institute at Warwick University expects a net 500,000 additional jobs by
2000, most of which will be part-time jobs taken by women in the service
sector. The female labour force is expected to grow by 500,000 over the next
decade.
The movement away from primary and manufacturing industries to the service
sector will continue, with manufacturing expected to lose another 600,000
jobs in the next decade. The new jobs will also continue the trend towards a
more divided labour market with many being low-pay/low-status jobs and
others being relatively high-pay/high-status.
The growth in clerical and secretarial work, which now accounts for just
over 4m jobs, will stop as a result of new technology, the institute says.
It expects an increase of about 150,000 clerical and secretarial jobs by the
end of the decade.
Skilled manual occupations will decrease by about 500,000 and plant and
machine operatives by about 400,000 by the end of the decade. The utilities
will lose an estimated 80,000 jobs by 2000, the report says, with the
biggest decrease in the electricity industry.
An increase of 750,000 posts is projected for managers and administrators
with a further 800,000 new jobs in professional and associate professional
and technical occupations such as laboratory assistants.
Part-time jobs accounted for the whole of the 1.2m increase in employment
between 1980 and 1990 and an extra 750,000 part-time posts are expected
before 2000.
The growth in self-employment, which in the 1980s was concentrated in
construction and certain parts of the service sector, is likely to increase
again following the decline in 1991 and last year. About 200,000 additional
self-employed jobs are expected before the end of the decade.
Institute for Employment Research, University of Warwick, Coventry, CV4 7AL.
Pounds 30.
</TEXT>
