<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Living costs show biggest fall for over 20 years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIVING COSTS have fallen more in the past year than at any time for more
than two decades, a study published today indicates.
The Reward Group, a consultancy specialising in pay and consumer studies,
calculates that in February a family with average needs in terms of housing
and consumer purchases required an income 5.1 per cent less than a year
previously to maintain its standard of living.
The year-on-year fall in living costs is the biggest since Reward started
its twice-yearly studies in 1972. This contrasts with the comparable
year-on-year decline of 0.7 per cent last August.
The findings support other indications of low inflationary conditions as a
result of the recession. While the muted level of price rises for many
consumer goods played a part in the overall fall in living costs, the
biggest factor was that housing costs for home owners fell by 19.7 per cent
in the year to February, mainly due to lower interest rates.
For the relatively small number of people who rent their homes from local
authorities housing costs rose 12.1 per cent because of higher rents.
Reward bases its results on a survey of average costs for a group of eight
hypothetical four-person families with different spending habits.
The annual income needed to support the families - which in each case
includes one adult in employment, a girl aged 10 and a boy aged eight -
works out at between Pounds 11,728 and Pounds 71,215, depending on
lifestyles.
In terms of the incomes needed for a set standard of living, Greater London,
Woking, Welwyn Garden City, Berkhamsted and Slough are the dearest places in
Britain while Northern Ireland, Peterhead, Thurso, Doncaster and Barnsley
are the cheapest.
The current downward pressures on the cost of living are, however, greatest
in Greater London, and lowest in Northern Ireland.
The report says that in the past 12 months food prices have not risen at all
while fuel costs have fallen by 0.5 per cent and transport costs have risen
by 3.5 per cent.
Cost of Living, Regional Comparisons April 1993. Reward, Diamond Way, Stone
Business Park, Stone, Staffordshire ST15 0SD. Annual subscription for two
copies Pounds 225.
</TEXT>
