<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Abbey puts home cover cost up 26%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABBEY National, the country's second-largest mortgage lender, announced
yesterday that it is to increase premiums on home contents insurance
policies by an average of 26 per cent, underlining the recent upward trend
in premium rates.
The rise follows increases elsewhere in the insurance market and comes after
a steep increase in theft costs. Last week the Association of British
Insurers announced that the the cost of theft claims in 1992 had risen 27
per cent on the previous year to Pounds 749m.
Although the increase appears to be slightly ahead of the trend of rises
elsewhere in the insurance market, the premiums charged until now by Abbey
are understood to be cheaper than its main rivals.
Abbey sells home structure and contents policies on behalf of a a 'panel' of
three insurers: Commercial Union, Royal Insurance and Legal &amp; General.
Earlier this year all three announced that they had increased premium rates
in most classes of insurance following heavy underwriting losses over the
past three years. The rises will take effect from the date that policies are
renewed.
However, customers renewing their policies between May and the end of the
year will also pay an average rise of 10 per cent announced in December last
year, taking their total increase to 37 per cent.
Mr Ambrose McGinn, head of product marketing at Abbey, said the increase was
'regrettable'.
</TEXT>
