<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Japanese steer around Maastricht storms:  The tortuous
progress of the Maastricht treaty in Britain is portrayed by the government
and its supporters as damaging to the national interest. Delays or
non-ratification, they say, threaten inward investment by presenting Britain
as 'half in and half out of Europe'.  But what do the inward investors
think?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ASK leading Japanese manufacturers if they are discouraged by the debate
over Maastricht from locating in Britain and some will betray annoyance at
the mere suggestion. Most will point to large strategic investments, already
made, to which they pledge commitment.
Toyota Motor in Tokyo is a good example. 'Considering the time, energy, and
money put into organising suppliers, distribution networks and shipping
ports, withdrawing from the UK is absolutely out of the question,' it said.
The company has invested more than Pounds 500m in a car plant in Derbyshire
and an engine plant in Wales.
Sony, the consumer electronics company, said there would be no change in
investment policies even if debates over Maastricht and the UK's return to
the European exchange rate mechanism continued. The company exports
televisions to continental Europe from its plant in Wales.
Sony said: 'It's probably unavoidable that every country has their
differences over further unification, but we're willing to wait three, five
or even 10 years.'
Toray, which manufactures synthetic fibres, has just completed its third
polyester plant in Nottingham. The company supplies Marks and Spencer, and
ships half of its products manufactured in the UK to continental Europe.
The company is philosophical: 'We don't think most of us will live to see
complete unification in Europe,' adding that many Japanese companies had set
up plants and distribution networks in the UK ahead of 1993. 'What happens
after that won't have much economic impact (on the company).'
Ricoh, the office machinery maker which manufactures copier machines and
parts in the UK, said: 'Politics and currencies are a cultural matter for
the countries involved,' stressing that the most important factor for
further investment was the economy and market demand.
For smaller Japanese companies yet to move into Europe, ratification of
Maastricht may not have as much weight as some Europhiles stress. A
researcher at Japan External Trade Organisation (Jetro), an affiliate of the
ministry of industry and trade, said the main criteria for choosing an area
for investment were market size and labour costs.
'This worry over Maastricht and Japanese companies is overdone. People see
great importance in the single market, where goods and services flow freely,
but prospects of what lies beyond that is not a major concern,' he added.
A Jetro survey of 433 Japanese companies with manufacturing or research and
development bases in Europe indicated that immediate reaction to the single
European market was muted, and that companies were still trying to assess
the effects.
Only 31.1 per cent said integration was having a positive effect on their
business, while 65.6 per cent indicated the effects were neither clearly
positive or negative.
On economic and currency unification, 72.5 per cent expect the process to be
delayed, while 21 per cent thought that not all EC members would
participate.
The survey also indicated that the UK remains the most favoured EC country -
27.7 per cent of 713 companies had chosen to locate manufacturing centres in
the UK.
The availability of English-speaking workers, distribution systems and
infrastructure are some of the reasons for the UK's popularity.
It is also worth noting that most investment decisions were made in the
1980s, when the UK's attitude towards Europe was unclear.
According to the Jetro report, the main reason for Japanese companies
cutting back on investments, or even pulling out of Europe, was the flagging
European economy. This suggests that Mr John Major, the prime minister, may
be successful in wooing more Japanese investment if the UK economy, and the
European market, pulls clear of recession.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
