<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Concerted action urged on exports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR RICHARD Needham, a trade and industry minister, moved yesterday to
encourage exporters to work more closely together in bidding for large
projects in foreign markets.
The government will aim to pinpoint 'national champions' to take the lead in
particular export sectors - including power, water, airports, transport and
oil and gas.
The action forms part of a wide-ranging effort to boost UK exports and
hinges on concern that contracts have been lost because UK companies have
been fighting against each other rather than against foreign competitors in
their efforts to win a contract.
Earlier this year North West Water and Thames Water lost a contract in
Buenos Aires to Generale des Eaux of France after competition between them
led to neither arranging export finance in time.
Mr Needham said he was 'determined to help create a unified British approach
to the challenge which the main project markets present. Companies need to
work together more effectively.' France and Japan in particular are seen as
having been effective in co-ordinating the efforts of local companies to win
large international contracts.
The change would 'provide focus and strategy and administrative structure to
back winners, and stop us murdering each other to the delight of our
competitors,' Mr Needham added.
The aim was to reorganise the Overseas Projects Board at the DTI, the job of
which is to ensure close links between the government and industry in bids
for big export projects.
New sector groups headed by businesspeople rather than government officials
would pinpoint UK export strengths in the sectors concerned, identify
priority export markets, seek joint ventures in infrastructure projects, and
look for opportunities for collaboration in developing countries in
particular as they privatised sectors of their economies.
The groups would identify circumstances where 'a single bid will improve the
UK's chances of securing major business (and will advise) on the selection
of one company or one group of companies to put forward the most effective
national bid when several UK companies are competing for a particular
project'.
Mr Needham said the reorganisation 'signals an important change of focus'.
It formed part of a wider aim to boost earnings from large contract exports
from an expected Pounds 10bn this year to Pounds 20bn by 2000.
Recently the government has taken steps to work with industry to aid
exporters. Additional export credit cover has been made available in
'concentrated markets' where UK exporters have been particularly successful
 -such as Indonesia, India, Malaysia, China and Hong Kong.
A campaign to boost exports to the US, launched a month ago, harnesses
proposals culled from industry (such as targeting 20 US sectors in which UK
exporters have strength) an education programme for exporters and 'strategic
alliances' introducing exporters to prospective US partners.
</TEXT>
