FT  06 APR 93 / Unions poised for more rail action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE disruption on the railways can be expected next week. The executive of
the Rail, Maritime and Transport Union meets today to decide on its next
move following last Friday's 24-hour stoppage on the railway network.
Unless British Rail guarantees no future compulsory redundancies, RMT looks
set to call another one-day strike, perhaps in mid-week. Tomorrow, the train
drivers' union Aslef will announce the result of a strike ballot. Its
leaders are confident of backing for a 24-hour stoppage.
RMT members at Sealink Stena ferries are also expected to join strike action
at ports while workers in the railway workshops are likely to join in the
next 24-hour stoppage.
The National Union of Mineworkers and London bus workers could also be
involved in further stoppages.
None of the unions can hold 24-hour stoppages indefinitely. By law they have
to hold further strike ballots within 28 days of their last ballots.
