<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Lib Dems 'living in sin with Labour'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservatives yesterday opened a second front in their campaign for next
month's county council elections in England and Wales by publishing their
own survey of party alliances in local government which denounces the
Liberal Democrats as 'Labour's stooges'.
Sir Norman Fowler, the Tory party chairman, described Liberal Democrat
councillors as 'living in sin with Labour up and down the land'.
There were, he said, no pacts between Liberal Democrats and Tories on county
councils. Tory central office admitted, however, that there was a formal
pact between Conservatives and Liberal Democrats in Wolverhampton borough
council, and that there might be one or two informal arrangements in other
non-county councils.
Reflecting the emphasis on the cost of local government, which is already
dominating the campaign, the Tory survey lists examples of Liberal
Democrats' support for Labour budgets in Avon, Bedfordshire, Cheshire and
Cumbria; and Liberal Democrats joining with Labour in Oxfordshire to defeat
Tory budget plans.
The Tories are also highlighting arrangements between the other parties
occurred where Conservatives are the largest single party.
Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, accused the Liberal Democrats
of striking 'cosy deals with Labour regardless of the clear wishes of the
local electorate'.
With one eye on the Liberal Democrat challenge to the Tories in the Newbury
parliamentary by-election - expected to coincide with the local elections -
Mr Howard cited the position on Berkshire county council, where the Liberal
Democrats had put Labour into power even though the Tories were by far the
largest party.
The Liberal Democrats are a focus of attack in these elections because they
are bound to perform better than when the 3,500 county council seats were
last contested. The 1989 local elections took place as the alliance between
the Liberals and the Social Democrats was falling apart.
