<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Time for audits 'not long enough'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUNIOR STAFF in accountancy firms believe that the time allowed for their
work for audit clients is not sufficient, the British Accounting Association
annual conference was told yesterday.
The findings, based on an initial analysis of 36 accountants at all levels
of seniority in response to a fictitious auditing case study, are contained
in a study by Mr John Dunn and Ms Anne Fergusson of the University of
Strathclyde.
Mr Dunn suggested that this might show the perceived level of low tendering
by accountants did not lead to short cuts in auditing but to greater
pressure on staff to maintain standards. But more senior managers and
partners believe that the time allocated through budgets was sufficient.
Mr Dunn stressed that he had found no evidence that time pressures on staff
reduced the quality of the audit. None of the respondents spent more than 8
hours a week on a client beyond the amount of time allocated. Most coped
with the extra workload by coming in early or working through their lunch
hour.
Partners in Irish accountancy firms back efforts to limit the threat of
litigation against them, the conference heard yesterday.
A survey by Mr Peter Green and Ms Jacqueline Granleese of the University of
Ulster found that accountants also recognised that any attempt to limit
their exposure would be seen as not providing the best protection for
investors using audited accounts.
</TEXT>
