FT  06 APR 93 / World Trade News: UK gives tied loan to Jakarta
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JAKARTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, yesterday signed a Pounds
65m concessional loan to Indonesia to fund a 65MW power station to be built
by a UK company in Samarinda, East Kalimantan.
The contract for the project has not been awarded but, under the terms of
the loan, it must go to a British company. Mr Hurd rebutted suggestions
that, by tying the aid, the UK government was undermining the principle of
free trade.
British exports to Indonesia grew 58 per cent to Pounds 312m last year,
while Indonesian exports to the UK rose 29 per cent to Pounds 536m.
Officials say the loan is a belated effort to promote UK companies in an
Indonesian sector in which Dollars 30bn of investment is planned in the
1990s.
