<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Community agrees copyright rules on crossborder TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMMON EC rules on copyright for television programmes transmitted across
borders via satellite and cable received broad approval from European
Community ministers yesterday.
The measure is aimed at filling a gap in the 1989 directive liberalising
crossborder broadcasts within the EC - the so-called 'television without
frontiers' directive, which came into force in October 1991 and contained no
reference to copyright protection.
Ministers responsible for the internal market agreed that the satellite and
cable companies responsible for transmitting the programmes would handle the
payment of royalties for cross-frontier broadcasts. The legal void has led
to confusion about who is responsible for paying copyright fees due on
satellite or cable broadcasts, with right-holders trying to collect
royalties from different companies in the member states where programmes are
received.
The directive will come into force on January 1, 1995, assuming it gets the
final legislative go-ahead from ministers and the European Parliament.
Separate draft legislation aims to harmonise differing national rules on the
duration of copyright protection.
Ministers postponed until June a decision on controversial measures aimed at
outlawing the sale of high-power motorcycles in the EC.
Motorcyclists demonstrated against the measure nearby, as ministers
discussed whether to limit the total power of the machines to 100 bhp.
The measure is part of a series of measures harmonising technical standards
for motorbikes. Advocates believe it will help improve road safety, but
Portugal, supported by the UK, yesterday proposed a five-year delay to allow
safety studies.
</TEXT>
