FT  06 APR 93 / Polish privatisation vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Poland's government won a clear majority in parliament at the weekend on a
first reading for its modified mass privatisation proposals involving the
transfer of 600 state sector enterprises into privately owned, foreign
managed National Investment Funds, Christopher Bobinski writes from Warsaw
The draft legislation now goes forward to committee stage where former
communist SLD deputies, who voted for a first reading after gaining
concessions from the government, are to resume pressure for further
amendments to the plan.
These focus on giving the enterprises selected for the scheme by the
government the right to opt out. The weekend vote puts the government's
privatisation strategy back on track for the moment, giving Mr Janusz
Lewandowski, the privatisation minister who last Friday survived a vote of
no confidence, a breathing space.
