<HEADLINE>
FT  06 APR 93 / Two former Italian PMs investigated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO FORMER Italian prime ministers, Mr Giulio Andreotti and Mr Arnaldo
Forlani, were served notice yesterday that they were under investigation for
alleged illicit financing of their Christian Democrat party.
The moves amount to a further widening of Italy's political corruption
scandal, which has led to the resignation of five ministers and
investigations into a large number of businessmen and politicians, including
former Socialist prime minister Bettino Craxi.
Mr Andreotti, who was advised by Palermo magistrates a week ago that he was
under investigation for alleged collusion with the Mafia, was warned of a
new inquiry into party funding by Milan magistrates.
Mr Forlani's inquiry is being carried out by Rome magistrates investigating
the awarding of contracts for road building by the state group Anas.
Until recently, Mr Forlani was secretary of the Christian Democrat party.
Last night Mr Andreotti told the Financial Times he could not recall the
transaction to which his inquiry relates, dating from the campaign for the
general election in April last year.
'I don't remember. . . But this was election time and you have to make a lot
of telephone calls,' he said. He was also dismissive of the moves to
incriminate him.
Parliament could meet today to consider whether to waive immunity on Mr
Andreotti, a life senator. Mr Andreotti's lawyers said yesterday: 'We are
completely and unconditionally at the disposition of the Milan magistrates
in whom we have absolute faith.'
This declaration contrasted with the vigorous reaction by Mr Andreotti and
the Christian Democrat party after Palermo magistrates sent a 256-page
dossier on the former premier to parliament last week.
Milan magistrates are understood to want to question Mr Andreotti about
payment of L250m (Pounds 114,000) allegedly arranged by him via his friend
Mr Giuseppe Ciarapico, owner of Roma football team and a prominent
financier, who was arrested on charges of fraud relating to a subsidiary of
state holding company Efim, now in liquidation.
The payment was allegedly made to help the Social Democrat party, one of the
Christian Democrats' coalition partners, in the 1992 elections. Mr Andreotti
is alleged to have orchestrated it.
</TEXT>
