<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 93 / NUM court threat over pit safety row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REFORM of the detailed health and safety legislation governing the operation
of British mines, which some private contractors believe is a necessary
condition for privatisation, could be blocked in the courts by the National
Union of Mineworkers.
The NUM has received legal advice which suggests that a judicial review
could successfully challenge any attempt by the government to reform the
relevant 'management of mines' part of the Mines and Quarries Act.
Health and safety in the mines is regulated by detailed provisions in the
act, which NUM officials say makes British mines three times safer than
mines in the US.
The roles of production supervisor and safety inspector are combined in
British mines through the deputy - represented by the union Nacods - ruling
out conflict between productivity and safety.
Reform proposals supported by the government and British Coal have been
presented to the Health and Safety Commission. These would abolish the
existing deputy function, replace statute with codes of practice and give
mine managers much more discretion in applying the rules.
Mr Peter McNestry, general secretary of Nacods, which is fighting the
proposed changes alongside the NUM, said: 'This is where the real battle
over labour relations in the mining industry is going to be.'
According to Mr Richard Budge, chief executive of RJB Mining, which is
negotiating to buy pits from British Coal, changing existing regulations is
a condition of making many pits profitable.
He does not believe the proposed changes would lead to a deterioration in
safety standards, but they would improve productivity. 'At the moment a hell
of a lot of people are paid to do nothing,' he said.
The proposed changes are likely to be presented to the government, employer
and trade union representatives on the Health and Safety Executive either
this month or next but the TUC representatives, Mr Alan Tuffin, the former
postal workers leader, and Mr Peter Jacques, a senior TUC official, are
certain to reject them in their present form.
The HSE has never over-ruled its union representatives on a matter of
substance. But the NUM believes that if the government decided to press
ahead with the changes in spite of a divided HSE, it could still be saved by
a clause in the Health and Safety at Work Act which requires any change to
health and safety laws to either maintain or improve safety standards.
One NUM official said: 'We might lose the battle over changing working
practices but our legal advice tells us that we can hold on to the safety
legislation.' That was rejected by Mr Budge, who said that the proposed
changes would not be seen by the judges as a deterioration in safety
standards.
British Coal and the unions are already in the middle of a consultation
exercise over working hours, prompted by the Department of Trade and
Industry. The NUM and Nacods will resist changes making 10-hour shifts and
Saturday working routine.
These changes have been accepted in most pits where the Union of Democratic
Mineworkers is dominant and at pit level in most NUM mines.
</TEXT>
<XX>
