<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 93 / Buy-out activity declines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGEMENT buy-out activity fell to a two-year low in the first quarter of
1993, with just seven large deals worth a total of Pounds 390m being
completed, accountants KPMG Peat Marwick said.
One reason for the decline was the cautious approach that managers and
vendors took to deals, said Mr Chris Beresford, head of management buy-outs
at the accountants, said. 'They are taking a belt and braces approach to
negotiations and to legal documentation. The larger deals are taking nine
months or even longer.'
The most recent quarter represents the lowest level of buy-out activity
since the first quarter of 1991, when seven deals worth Pounds 120m were
completed.
However, it compares poorly with the first quarter of last year, when 16
deals worth Pounds 640m were completed.
The largest deal completed in the first 1993 quarter was that of McDonnell
Douglas Information Systems, valued at about Pounds 200m. Other deals
included Colas, a road services and building materials company, from Shell
for Pounds 72m; Ashbourne Homes for Pounds 53m; and British International
Helicopters for Pounds 33m. In roughly equal measure the buy-outs involved
purchases from receivers, corporate restructurings and disposals of non-core
activities.
In total, Peat Marwick calculates that 130 deals worth Pounds 570m were
completed in the first quarter of 1993 compared with a total of 520 worth
Pounds 3bn in the whole of 1992.
</TEXT>
