<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 93 / Report endorses private prison
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOLDS, Britain's first privately managed prison for nearly 200 years,
combines successful features with causes for concern, a Prison Reform Trust
report says today.
The trust says that available evidence about Wolds, opened on Humberside a
year ago to accommodate remand prisoners, 'contradicts both the view of the
apologists for privatisation and the wilder claims of the prison's critics'.
It says the prison, managed under a Home Office contract by Group 4 Remand
Services, offers prisoners up to 14 hours a day out of their cells and
better entitlement to visits than comparable prisons. Staff generally
treated inmates in a 'just, fair and humane way' and were responsive to
reasonable requests.
But, says the report, the level of incidents and disturbances at Wolds was
worse than national averages. Use of drugs by prisoners was a problem in
many prisons, but the trust understood that at Wolds the level of the
problem was 'alarming and getting worse'.
Public accountability was hindered by the fact that financial details of
Group 4's contract with the Home Office were confidential. 'The company is
not required to produce an annual report to the Home Office and, if it was,
presumably this too would have been secret. In any event, proper
value-for-money comparisons cannot be made.'
A second privately managed prison, Blakenhurst, Hereford and Worcester, is
about to open, and later this month ministers will consider public and
private bids to run Strangeways prison in Manchester. Bids to manage the new
Doncaster prison, and possibly others, are likely to be invited later this
year.
Wolds Remand Prison: A First Year Report, PRT, 59 Caledonian Road, London N1
9BU. Pounds 2.50.
