<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 93 / Labour to float plan for two-tier boards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONCEPT of the European-style company, with a two-tier board, is being
canvassed by Labour as part of its drive to bring more 'long-termism' into
British industry.
Labour sees some merits in the German model, in which a firm's governance is
split between a supervisory board responsible for monitoring management and
setting policy, and an executive board dealing with the management of the
policy. Worker directors would be elected to the supervisory board, to which
the executive board would be accountable.
The idea is expected to be floated tomorrow by Mr Stuart Bell, the
opposition's City spokesman, in a speech to the British Accounting
Association. He is expected to argue that one of the benefits of this form
of organisation is that the company is less susceptible to hostile
takeovers.
This accent on long-term planning in industry is reflected in Labour's new
policy paper to be launched tomorrow. Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and
industry secretary, will use the discussion paper Making Britain's Future,
as the basis for consultation with commerce and industryover the coming
months.
One of its elements is a proposal to shift the burden of proof when hostile
takeovers are referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission so that the
takeover rather than the defence has to be justified.
The argument for a takeover would have to take in not only the financial
rationale and the benefits to the companies involved, but include the wider
impact of the deal on the economy and whether the takeover was in the
national interest.
The paper envisages that Britain's manufacturing base could be broadened by
ensuring that pension funds could have a greater emphasis on industrial
investment - and perhaps by diverting some building society funds to
industry rather than property.
It also proposes a change in the law to prevent banks forcing the closure of
companies that could be revived.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
