<TEXT>
A CONSERVATIVE think-tank is warning that the government could face 'a
second coal crisis' over its rail privatisation plans unless imbalances
between rail and road transport are addressed, Richard Tomkins writes.
The Bow Group says failure to put the financing of railways and roads on a
similar footing will mean that many lines will be unable to compete with
roads. It says: 'The parallels with the rigged market in electricity and its
impact on demand for coal are striking.'
Railway freight and passenger traffic is being lost to the roads because
road users are not required to pay full costs.
