<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 93 / Revised small-business loan scheme delayed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS SAY that the revamped small-business loan guarantee scheme, announced
in the Budget last month as one of the measures to speed recovery from the
recession, will not be ready until October this year.
In addition, the scheme's new Pounds 250,000 ceiling will not be universally
available, applying only to existing businesses. Start-ups will be limited
to the scheme's old ceiling of Pounds 100,000.
The scheme enables small businesses to raise bank loans when security is not
available. Under the existing scheme the government guarantees up to 70 per
cent of a loan and the borrower pays a 2.5 percentage point premium on the
interest rate.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, announced that the level of eligible loan
would rise by Pounds 150,000, with the maximum guaranteed portion rising to
85 per cent.
The premium will be cut to 1.5 per cent for variable-rate loans and 0.5 per
cent for fixed-rate loans.
About 20 lenders, including the large clearing banks, many smaller banks and
small-business advisory and finance bodies, take part in the scheme.
The delay in the start of the new scheme was greeted with surprise and
dismay by corporate finance advisers. Mr Peter Folkman, head of North of
England Ventures, a venture-capital fund backed by Schroders, said banks had
been telling applicants they would have to wait until October.
The Department of Trade and Industry said: 'We are not so pessimistic as to
think it will be October. We think it will be brought in sooner than that,
but we cannot be certain when at this stage. It takes time to make the
arrangements with the banks.'
But Mr Ian Templeton, senior partner of the Manchester office of Stoy
Hayward, the accountancy firm, said that DTI officials in Sheffield had told
him the scheme would start in October.
North of England Ventures had hoped that the scheme would enable Panel
Signs, a Nottingham management buy-out in which it has Pounds 550,000
invested as equity for a 60 per cent stake, to trade its way out of trouble.
Now, it said, the company would almost certainly close this month - with the
loss of 60 jobs - because it could not bridge the gap to the new scheme's
introduction. The company makes illuminated signs for businesses such as
supermarkets and filling stations.
The DTI confirmed yesterday that the existing ceiling would apply to
start-ups, and that the new limit was to help established businesses.
</TEXT>
