<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 93 / Pensions blow to government contracting-out plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROGRAMME of market-testing public services faces another serious
setback after a ruling from the attorney-general that contractors will have
to provide 'broadly comparable' pension rights in many cases where staff are
transferred from the public sector.
Under Transfer of Undertakings (Tupe) regulations, which apply to many
contracts, companies are obliged to retain the existing workforce on the
same terms and conditions. But most companies had assumed, encouraged by the
government, that big savings could be made in pension payments.
Many contractors have only been able to take over profitably services in the
National Health Service, local government and the Civil Service by offering
less generous pension arrangements than the typically index-linked public
sector pension.
But Sir Nicholas Lyell, attorney-general, has upheld his department's advice
on Tupe, ignored when granting most previous contracts, that contractors
should give comparable pension rights when taking over staff from government
departments.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, had suggested that
departments should avoid giving such guidance on Tupe. Sir Nicholas has told
her that advice previously given by law officers, that pensions were covered
by the regulations, was correct.
His insistence on the law officers' view follows guidance from Mr William
Waldegrave, civil service minister, that occupational pensions were not
affected by the regulations, a view echoed by the Department of Health.
Some contractors, when told of Sir Nicholas's ruling, reacted with dismay,
though others said the definition of 'comparable' might provide some room
for less generous benefits.
Mr Simon Cox, managing director of ISS Mediclean, which has 80 cleaning
contracts with the NHS, said: 'This is the crunch. It is just about possible
to cope with the other aspects of Tupe and run a profitable business. But if
we have to provide fully-funded, index-linked, pensions, it becomes
impossible.'
Typically, in the funding of a public service pension the employer and
employee between them pay in up to 13 per cent of salary each year compared
with less than 10 per cent in a small private sector service company.
Some of the contractors pay no pensions at all. A trade union official said
the government could face a 'deluge' of retrospective claims from people who
had had to accept reduc-tions in pension provision.
Mr Padraig Flynn, EC social affairs commissioner, has confirmed that Sir
Nicholas's ruling is correct by stating in a letter to Mr Lyndon Harris, the
Labour MEP, that the Acquired Rights Directive, on which Tupe is based, does
extend protection to occupational pension schemes.
Mr Tino Hernandez, head of research at the CPSA public service union said:
'The last avenue through which private contractors might have been able to
make savings to enable them to beat in-house bids has effectively been cut
off.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
