<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Fiat executive answers charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Riccardo Ruggeri, chief executive of New Holland, Fiat's London-based
agricultural machinery and earth-moving equipment venture with Ford,
yesterday presented himself to Milan magistrates to answer charges of
alleged corruption, Robert Graham reports from Rome.
Milan magistrates had issued an arrest warrant for Mr Ruggeri on March 24
and are understood to be questioning him about the period when he was
working in Iveco, Fiat's commercial vehicules subsidiary. Iveco's Milan
concessionaire is alleged to have paid 4 per cent of a 15 per cent discount
on a bus sale to the Milan municipality into a Swiss bank account, for use
by Italian political parties.
On Thursday, an arrest warrant was issued for Mr Mauro Bertini, managing
director of Fiat Avio, the Turin auto group's turbines subsidiary,
concerning some L6bn (Pounds 2.5m) alleged to have been paid to the
Christian Democrat and Socialist parties so as to secure a turbine contract
in a power station. This followed the arrest of an intermediary and Avio
consultant, Mr Roberto Araldi, on Wednesday. Mr Bertini is believed to be
abroad.
Mr Mario Artali, managing director of the state food group SME, was arrested
in Rome on a charge of illegal party financing, according to the Italian
news service Ansa. SME, part of Italy's Iri holding company, is one of the
first companies slated for privatisation under a plan by Italy to sell off
much of its state sector.
