<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / UK Company News: MB-Caradon disposes of French packaging
stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MB-CARADON, the building products and security printing group, yesterday
sold its 25.3 per cent stake in CarnaudMetalbox the French packaging group,
raising FFr3.9bn (Pounds 473m) before costs.
The group is expected to use the money to finance acquisitions but said
yesterday it did 'not have any major acquisition in mind at present'. Even
so a number of companies in the building materials sector saw their share
prices rise in anticipation. MB-Caradon's shares rose 2p to 320p.
Mr Peter Jansen, chief executive, said 'the disposal gives us substantial
cash resources. We are confident that we can deploy these into businesses
that we manage, and whose cashflows we control, for the long-term benefit of
our shareholders'.
The buyers of the holding of 20.5m shares, included CGIP, the French
industrial holding company which added 7 per cent to its existing 25.3 per
cent stake.
The interest dates back to the merger in 1989 of Metalbox Packaging, part of
the former MB Group which then bought Caradon, and Carnaud, the French group
in which CGIP was a large investor.
Although CarnaudMetalbox had a somewhat shaky start, new management has
improved profits in the last 18 months and the share price has risen. On
Wednesday it announced results for 1992 which showed net profits up by 15
per cent to FFr976m.
The stake was valued in MB-Caradon's 1991 accounts at Pounds 337.5m, and it
contributed Pounds 31.8m to profits that year. But the dividend received in
1991 was only Pounds 7.8m.
Mr Jansen said he had been under pressure from shareholders to sell the
stake since 1990, when he would have been glad to get Pounds 250m for it.
In February MB-Caradon called a meeting of shareholders for March to give it
authority to sell the stake. Despite this signal that the shares were for
sale, Mr Jansen said that there had been no firm offers for the complete
hold-ing.
Now, he said, it was 'cyclically a good time' to buy building products
businesses in the UK, but that MB-Caradon would also be looking in
continental Europe and North America. With its borrowing facilities and the
cash, it could spend Pounds 1bn.
Although the deal will give CGIP 32.3 per cent of the shares, it will hold
46 per cent of the votes in CarnaudMetalbox because shares held for more
than two years have double voting rights.
Parfinance, a company controlled by Mr Paul Desmarais, the Canadian
businessman, and Mr Albert Frere, the Belgian businessman, bought 6 per
cent. Parfinance was found by CGIP which wanted an 'associate investor' but
the two holdings are not deemed by the French stock exchange to constitute a
concert party. The remaining shares were placed by Warburg.
Warburg bought 10m shares at FFr190 each and placed them at FFr197, against
Thursday's close of FFr217, taking a gross profit of FFr70m.
See Lex
</TEXT>
