<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Clients of factor company investigated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON and ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Inland Revenue is monitoring the circumstances of the collapse of two
companies which had business dealings with London and Provincial Factors,
the debt trading company that failed five weeks ago.
In an unusual move a tax investigator attended creditors' meetings which
were held to wind up Brentford Radio Cars, a car hire company, and
Europublishing, both operating in London. The investigator, from the
Revenue's special office in Edinburgh which examines cases outside the scope
of local tax offices, has also joined the creditors' committees monitoring
the liquidation of the two companies.
The collapse of London and Provincial Factors with net debts of more than
Pounds 7m surprised other companies in the industry.
Debt trading companies - known as factors - provide services which range
from taking over the management of their clients' sales ledgers to lending
them a percentage of the value of their invoices. Clients are usually liable
for bad debts and it is rare for a factor to go bust.
Matters relating to LPF's collapse are also being examined by the Fraud
Squad. It is understood that the squad will decide whether to launch a
formal investigation later this month.
LPF's receivership caused difficulties for up to 40 of its clients.
Mr Stephen Mills, managing director of Leo Lithographics, a small printing
business, said his company faces collapse within seven days because its
invoices are now held by LPF's receivers, two accountants from Grant
Thornton.
The receivers said: 'All the clients of LPF have been given the opportunity
of getting back invoices sold to the factoring company on payment of the
amounts advanced to them by LPF.' The receivers said they 'have agreed a
number of deals on this basis. In the case of the Leo company it has been
unable to raise the necessary funding'.
LPF's collapse has prompted the Association of British Factors and
Discounters to urge the Bank of England to regulate independent factors,
such as LPF, more tightly. The association's members account for more than
90 per cent of the industry's turnover. LPF is not a member.
At least five companies, which were all clients of LPF, are known to have
gone into liquidation since July 1990, owing more than Pounds 3m to the
factoring company, according to liquidators' estimates.
The remaining three are Isleworth Press (formerly Recorder Newspapers plc),
Embassy Radio Cars, Boston Publications (formerly Recorder Newspapers Ltd)
and Heathrow Engine Centre.
At the Brentford Radio Cars creditors' meeting, Mr Ian Lowe, an executive of
the car hire company, listed several assets which he said he believed should
not be included in the company's statement of affairs because they were
secured against the personal assets of the executives. These included a
yacht and three properties.
Europublishing's directors said in their written report to creditors that
the company's liquidation had been precipitated by LPF's receivership. They
claimed the factoring company owed Europublishing more than Pounds 4m in
losses suffered because of the need for a speedy sale to an unconnected
newspaper group.
A spokesman for the receivers of LPF said: 'Far from LPF causing the failure
of Europublishing, LPF actually provided Europublishing with more funds than
they were entitled to under the factoring agreement.
'In fact, based on figures prepared by the company and on information
provided to the receivers, the receivers believe LPF is looking at a
shortfall in excess of Pounds 500,000 on this account.'
Europublishing, which traded as Recorder, lists creditors including Mr Mario
Nicolaides and Mr Michael Rowan, both former directors of Recorder
Newspapers Ltd, which changed its name to Boston Publications before its
collapse in April 1991.
Mr Rowan was also until last summer a director of Embassy Radio Cars (1981),
which changed its name to Brentford Radio Cars last month.
Mr Nicolaides was sentenced to 80 hours community service for fraudulent
trading in a separate company last month.
</TEXT>
