<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Azerbaijan declares emergency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FORMER Soviet republic of Azerbaijan declared a state of emergency
yesterday, after gains by Armenian forces in battles just inside Azerbaijani
territory, agencies report.
President Abulfaz Elchibey ordered a curfew and travel restrictions, and
banned political activity that might destabilise the situation. The
emergency would apply throughout Azeri territory for three months.
Mr Elchibey had earlier sent a message to the Russian and US presidents, and
called on democratic nations to denounce the Armenians as aggressors.
An Azeri defence ministry spokesman said Armenian forces had captured 25
villages in western Azerbaijan and reached the regional centre of
Kelbadzhar. He said the Armenians were fighting inside the town limits.
More than 2,500 people have been killed in five years of Azeri-Armenian
fighting, the deadliest and longest conflict in the former Soviet Union.
Most of the unrest has been near the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh,
but fighting has often spilled into border regions of the two states.
