<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Businessmen who bore for Europe: Dominic Lawson asks why
employees of multi-nationals care so little for their democratic birthright
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINIC LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I HAVE always enjoyed talking to businessmen. About business, that is. When
people know what they are talking about, it always pays to listen and learn.
But when businessmen get on to politics, they tend to divide into two
categories, neither of them edifying or instructive.
On the one hand there are the saloon bar bar gin-and-it bores whose views
are indistinguishable from the traditional taxi-driver's, but without the
pithy articulacy of the cockney cabbie.
On the other hand there are those businessmen, normally employees of very
big companies, whose political views, such as they are, seem to be entirely
conditioned by their corporation's business objectives. As individual
citizens they have virtually no political views at all.
One can see this most clearly in the debate over the Maastricht Treaty on
European Union (to give it its proper name). Almost limitless seem to be the
articles by businessmen denouncing notions of sovereignty as 'sentimental',
and demanding the speedy implementation of moves towards European currency
and political union.
They think, with their employee's hat on, that it will make running their
business so much simpler. No need to hedge against nasty foreign exchange
risks in the European market, no need to bribe, sorry, wine and dine, lots
of silly ministers, when you will only have to br . . . wine and dine one
commissioner in Brussels. And thus they are quite happy, as citizens of one
country, to sign away the absolute right to vote in or out of office those
who decide how much tax they will pay, those who decide what battles their
armed forces will fight.
It is, I suspect, no accident, that the businessmen who have such a limited
vision of political morality tend to be managers in multi-national
corporations. They spend so much of their time flying from one time zone to
another, living off airline food, staying at hotels of truly international
colourlessness, talking only to other people with the same way of life, that
they have quite lost a sense of the intrinsic differences between countries.
Business class air-conditioning has frozen their synapses and jet lag has
entered their souls.
The Confederation of British Industry, increasingly dominated by the larger
multinational companies, has become particularly addled. It was almost
comical, and certainly tragic, how that organisation loudly and persistently
defended the notion that sterling should not be allowed to fall below
DM2.78, even as that rate was demolishing the earnings of its members and
the domestic interest rates required to support the rate were becoming
politically unsustainable. And all was justified because this havoc was
deemed essential to keep Britain on the fabled 'fast train to Europe.'
ICI had been a particular supporter of this doomed policy, and it was hard
to stomach its chairman's recent statement, as the company laid off 4,000,
to the effect that the newly competitive pound would help to restore its
business opportunities. If I was one of those 4,000 I would have liked to
see Sir Denys Henderson next to me in the queue at the Jobcentre. His
company was at it again last week. An article by ICI's chief economist, one
Richard Freeman, in the Evening Standard, went under the strap line 'The
benefits of a complete Single European Market are too large to be put at
risk by sentiments about UK sovereignty.' Freeman showed he is not
sentimental about sovereignty. The 'S' word appeared only once in an article
of about 1,500 words.
As Lord Stoddart responded next day: 'How well it shows that big business is
more concerned with profit than democracy, freedom and self-government. It
is surely no coincidence that it is big business in Hong Kong which is
opposed to Mr Patten's democratic reforms and big business here in Britain
that wishes to give away to remote institutions those democratic freedoms we
have left.'
We should not be unjust. Perhaps we have left out a third category of
businessman, who is neither a saloon bar bore, nor a deracinated jobsworth.
He is the one who knows that the drive towards European federalism is
unworkable but is damned if he is going to stick his neck out and say so in
public. As has been said before now, capital is a coward.
Dominic Lawson is Editor of The Spectator.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
