<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Interview: Trial separation from a claustrophobic God -
After seven years as a nun, Karen Armstrong turned her back on the Catholic
heirarchy. Now she has rediscovered her faith in a different kind of deity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIRTY YEARS ago, Karen Armstrong got married. She borrowed some white
winklepickers and cut her hair with rusty scissors. She vowed to give
everything to her groom and she struggled with the relationship for seven
years, striving to obey, humiliating herself, even whipping her own flesh in
an attempt to become more obedient.
The marriage ended in divorce as Armstrong, by then ill with undiagnosed
epilepsy, began to doubt if her groom existed at all. Now well again, and
writing books in a pleasant little house in the north London suburb of East
Finchley, she has just finished the biography of her ex-husband, whom she
thought she had lost forever. Yet, in researching The History of God, she
has found 'Him' again.
Armstrong joined her strict Roman Catholic order as a novice nun of just 17.
As the 1960s swung outside, she was on her hands and knees wearing scratchy
underpants, engaged in a search for the supreme being. She says: 'At
adolescence, when you are so bogged down in misery about your own
confusions, the idea of losing yourself in God and finding an enhanced self
seemed enormously attractive.'
Instead of losing herself, she found she was confronted endlessly by her own
inadequacies. 'The convent made us so concerned about ourselves, there was
no way we could have a religious experience.'
If the search for God in the convent was painful, life outside was even
worse. 'It was hard, because people assumed it would be great to be out. But
I was just sick with grief, and very ill for about six years. I was grieving
the loss of God, of me, of a whole life.'
In leaving the convent to study English at Oxford, she traded one
claustrophobic institution for another. 'I found Oxford was a highly unkind
society, where distinguished academics sat around bitching about each
other.' In spite of her dismissiveness, the university has left its mark:
her intense manner, antique furniture, books, black leggings and the
Cuban-heel boots tell more of the stylish intellectual than the ex-nun.
After a few years outside, she gave up Catholicism and started to think of
herself as an atheist. 'It was a great relief to be rid of the big brother
noting your every failure. A god who is organising Bosnia, the Sudan,
Somalia - frankly, I don't want to know anything about him or her.' Faced
with cruelty around her both on a big and a small scale, she became obsessed
with the need for kindness. 'Over the years, compassion became more and more
central to me,' she says, managing to sound neither goody-goody nor pompous.
Yet, after steeping herself in 4,000 years of man's thoughts on God, she
found she remains a believer. She rejects much of Christianity and is
opposed vehemently to anything that smacks of doctrine or idolatry.
Nowadays, she describes her self as a 'freelance monotheist.'
The research for her book showed her that the quest for a supreme being was
flawed at the outset. To her surprise, she says she found that all the
wisest thinkers in Christianity, Judaism and Islam had reached the same
conclusion independently: that God is not - contrary to popular belief - an
objective reality at all.
'God is an experience of something larger. It is not just within - it is
something beyond. The religions are an endless dance between an immanence
and a transcendence, something that pulls us beyond our little prejudices
and which offer a challenge.' This transcendence struck her first when she
was reading TS Eliot and John Donne as a teenager. 'Poetry and music did it
for me. A sense of something beautiful, just out of reach.'
That sense now comes to her through study, and she likens herself to the
black-coated Jews who stand muttering over their prayer books. It is just as
well she likes study, as she has much ahead: in conversation, almost every
fresh subject suggests a theme for a future book. Once she has finished
writing about the ordination of women, she plans to tackle the rise of
fundamentalism world-wide, the role of women in religion, and a history of
religious fanatics in the US.
She says the point of religion is to hold us in a state of wonder. It should
help us to ask questions: the problems arise when it starts to answer them.
'A lot of religion crowds out that wonder by giving doctrinal answers that
explain everything. Who is God?' Impatiently, she rattles off catechisms
learnt as a child as if they were, self-evidently, nonsense. 'One of the
mistakes of western Christianity is to put so much emphasis on extraordinary
doctrines about God somehow being three in one, and on lengthy creeds about
the resurrection and life everlasting.'
Most people - she says 99 per cent of Americans and two-thirds of Britons
claim to believe in God - remain stuck with a notion of Him learnt in
childhood. 'Our ideas of other disciplines become more sophisticated as we
grow up, but most people's ideas of God - including those of atheists - have
remained at that infantile level.'
Having shunned the 'multifarious and bizarre things' that Christianity
expects people to believe, Armstrong has picked her own beliefs from
different religions at different times. A bit of Greek Orthodoxy here, some
Buddhism there, and a sprinkling of mysticism over everything. She also
admires Islam. 'In the Moslem creed, there is no divinity but God and
Mohammed is the prophet. That's it,' she says, approvingly.
'A cross-fertilisation of ideas is now just what is needed to give tired old
monotheism a shot in the arm. Now, in the 20th century, you do not have to
be a Jew or Christian just because you were born in Europe. We have
discovered through better communications that all these religions have been
doing the same thing. They will talk about God, or they will not, but the
experience and the ideals are pretty much the same.'
Yet, Armstrong is not optimistic: the rise of fundamentalism in all three
religions shows people digging themselves deeper into their narrow trenches.
She does not notice the western church looking outside for fresh ideas. 'The
churches, as a whole, have a great deal of re-thinking to do. Look at all of
them quarrelling about the ordination of women - where is their compassion
for a suffering world?'
Throughout the discussion, it is to the issue of compassion that she returns
constantly. This, she says, is the acid test of all religions; without it, a
religion has failed. 'All the great religions of the world have found that
the ability to integrate your religious experience with normal mundane life,
and become more compassionate, is what matters.'
Had she known all this three decades ago, might she have stayed in the
convent? Armstrong shakes her head, emphatically. She believes some people
are natural nuns - but not her. It was not that convent life was unendurably
hard, nor that she was expected to behave as a submissive Victorian woman.
(She joined just before the Second Vatican Council swept away some of the
repressive practices that she refers to, politely, as 'clutter').
One problem was celibacy. 'It's the loneliness. That is the side of celibacy
that is hard. Even though you are in the middle of a community, you are
deeply alone.' Another was having to live with a group of people she had not
chosen. 'In the convent, there were some nuns who did not love people but
who loved the cat. They had started grabbing back little satisfactions to
take the place of big things. I knew that would happen to me.'
Apparently, many other inmates reached the same conclusion: there was an
exodus from the convents in the 1960s and 1970s, and many of the orders -
like hers - set up to do good works have had to re-define their role. 'A lot
of the so-called good works are now performed by the state. The orders that
are getting the same number of vocations are the contemplative orders. They
are doing very well.'
She thinks those kind of orders will always do well. In delving into the
past 4,000 years, she has found religious communities seeding themselves in
all ages and all societies. 'There always have been, and always will be,
people that have the need and the talent for contemplation, just as there
are people who are going to want to write poetry or become musicians.'
If not a contemplative, then, was she just an escapee from the real world?
She looks impatient. 'There is too much unhealthy concentration on motives.
We are all drop-outs. Marriage can be a great selfish act of dropping out.
Some people put up the net curtains and shut the world out.' Although she
has never been married, she makes the observation without bitterness. 'I
still live alone because I am that kind of person. I suppose I am still
looking for something. I went into a convent looking for something and here
I am, at the grand old age of nearly 50, still writing books about God.'
Surely, though, she is nearer her destination now? Not at all. Perhaps it is
more a case of having found her means of transport. 'Buddha said that
questions about the ultimate reality were improper. The most he could say
was that there is a shore on the other side of the river and give you a raft
to take you over. That is what religion should be.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-16725</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDDAIAFWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930403
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Arts: Essay in diversity - Concert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SZYMANOWSKI'S Stabat mater (1925-6) and Bartok's Miraculous Mandarin (1926)
are unlikely components of the same concert programme. Both were written
during the same decade, and both employ a chorus (the Bartok confines its to
a brief passage of wordless humming) and a large modern orchestra.
Otherwise, their attributes could not be more dissimilar: the Szymanowski
prayer a rapt re-discovery of an 'archaic', specifically Polish quality of
spiritual intensity, the Bartok ballet-score a penny-dreadful tale of urban
violence clothed in luridly colourful musical modernism.
It was, therefore, the special, splendid achievement of Simon Rattle and his
City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra and Chorus to make such a success - in
part and sum equally - of their inclusion in Thursday's concert at the
London Festival Hall. The planning was aided, of course, by the larger
thematic concerns of the South Bank series enclosing the event: this was the
latest on the 'Toward the Millennium' schedule, which is currently focusing
on all the diverse, complex and often wildly contradictory musical of the
1920s.
A pointed essay in extreme diversity was, indeed, what we were given: along
with Bartok and Szymanowski, Busoni's subtly piquant New Classicism was also
represented (by two instrumental sections from the opera Doctor Faust) and
Sibelius's final refinement of the late-Romantic symphonic ideal (by the
Seventh Symphony).
But mainly it was the extraordinarily unstinted advocacy of Rattle and the
profoundly musical playing and singing of his Birmingham forces that
achieved appropriate weight and balance in each of the concert's sharply
contrasted items. On this occasion, the Bartok particularly exposed a
shortage of fibre in string tone; it could also be argued - but not, I hope,
too stringently - that Rattle's enthusiasm for the glorious 'arrival' of the
Sibelius finale was advertised a degree too early and too obviously. Between
soulless international-orchestral virtuosity and the kind of impassioned
commitment to musical meaning on offer here, there has seldom seemed a
greater or more illuminating difference.
</TEXT>
