<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Arts: Springboard for 'Somewhere'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNDER the aegis of its Springboards Festival, the National Theatre is
staging a series of new plays at its own Cottesloe Theatre, in collaboration
with the Royal Court Upstairs and Bush Theatres in London, and with studios
at the Leicester Haymarket Theatre, the Birmingham Repertory Theatre and the
Salisbury Playhouse. This welcome association comprises nine plays, and
continues until July. Springboards opens at the Liverpool Playhouse Studio
with Somewhere by Judith Johnson.
The series looks diverse and exciting, and should be a fillip for new
writing. The regional work will arrive in April and May at the Cottesloe
sure of a venue; while in Leicester and Liverpool, where two of the plays
open, the productions will have the prospect and purpose of a London run.
At Liverpool, Somewhere is an affecting, discursive play about the effects
of the 1980s on people now. It opens on school leaving day, when the role
models were Sid Vicious and Debbie Harry, and when every cigarette was
clamped between thumb and second finger and smoked with an anarchic squint.
The music was Punk and the tattoos, like the entertainment, home-made.
The play follows a group of teenagers through a month's partying, and fixes
on the loose relationship between Dawn, a strong, wild girl revelling in her
capacity to shock, and Lee, a quiet manic likely to burst into violence.
Around them are victims, co-dependents and one Thatcherite - 'I want to be
an entrepreneur, me.' Lee becomes a soldier throughout the 1980s, demobbed
after Desert Storm; Dawn becomes a prostitute in King's Cross and now
Amsterdam, where the two meet ten years on in a brothel, still in love.
Somewhere tries to uncover the past while developing a situation in the
present. The balance is not yet right, tilted more toward reminiscence -
fine 1980s retrospective - than current interchange. Perhaps a larger
theatre and a revolving stage would juxtapose past and present more starkly.
Since no plot imposes a structure on the piece, the pacing of scenes is
crucial. Here, the lighting (Mark Rickards) and the direction (Polly Teale)
could drive the action faster and focus it sharper. The simple, strong
staging works well in the studio space: a lounge becomes a park and a
coffee-table a coffin within a wire fence set.
Johnson's dialogue is funny, brash, bawdy and clever, but it leaves too
little unsaid. However, she has written two fine strong parts for Katrina
Levon (Dawn) and John Hannah (Lee); both act them with power and conviction,
and it is these performances which carry the play. Other highlights include
Karl Draper as a sad thug too timid to leave his home town and Ian Dunn as
Barry the barman, now the nightclub entrepreneur he always dreamed of
becoming.
Liverpool Playhouse Studio until April 17; Cottesloe Theatre, London from
April 24 to May 15. Information about Springboards on 071-633-0880
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
