<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Arts: Good, bad and smudgy - Video
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'A movie on video cassette always looks better than it is, but is somehow
less interesting, whereas in the cinema films often look worse than they
are, but are more interesting. You figure it out.' Gore Vidal, quoted in
'Films On Video: The Essential 100', a Sight And Sound Magazine special
supplement.*
Dear Gore, I've already figured it out. Like many of your apercus it isn't
true, but it is interestingly untrue. It is the remark - pardon me - of a
literate humanist and an audio-visual philistine.
Movies on video look 'better' in the sense that by snipping screen ratios
and blurring pictorial values they direct the viewer's attention almost
exclusively onto the main characters and what they are saying or doing.
Ergo: the story becomes all foreground and no background. It may seem to
have more momentum - even more 'style' - while being less interesting
graphically and subtextually.
Correspondingly, a film on the large screen can 'look worse' to someone
fixated merely on that character interaction. (All those square feet of
otiose countryside in John Ford])
Am I being fair? Please get back to me if you think not. Respectfully, NA
I was roused to this open letter not just by Mr V's remark but by the place
where it was quoted. Sight And Sound's '100 Best' is a good news/bad news
enterprise. The good news is that it is a priceless guide to the best
classics now available on cassette: everything from Broken Blossoms to
Raging Bull via B. Keaton, S. Eisenstein, O. Welles and B. Bertolucci. Short
credits and appraisals accompany each film; mini-essays offer guidance to
different decades and genres.
But the bad news: no one warns you what kind of experience to expect.
Critics usually obtain good copies of videos. (So, I imagine, does Mr
Vidal). But the average punter can be in quite a different boat. Sticking
his pole where'er he can in the video-market waters, he either pulls it up
to discover a lot of mud and weeds, or he cannot pull it up at all and falls
into the river.
The second experience is common. Few video stores stock anything resembling
Sight And Sound's august pantheon. 'La Regle Du Jeu, sir? Does that star
that Chuck Norris or Jean-Claude Van Damme?' So the punter, especially if he
lives far from London or other major cities, tumbles headlong into the
compulsive, hopeless, finally drowning search for That Video.
Then again he might not want the video when he does find it. Last week at a
major London store I bought a copy of a Famous John Ford Film (Pounds 5.99,
Video Collection). When I played it, expecting two hours of pictorial
uplift, I could not believe what I saw. Filthy, mud-dredged colours; fuzzy
resolution; muffled sound. John Wayne was, I think, that pink blob swaying
across screen from left to right; and that chestnut-coloured mass beneath
him could have been a horse, then again it could have been Maureen O'Hara.
We began with a letter, so let us end with one.
Dear Sight And Sound, We greatly appreciate your attention to video in
general and your new library-building supplement in particular. But as a
monitor of our screen culture, you should be more conscientious in warning
readers about how debased the video experience can be in the hands of some
modern video companies. Why should the customer put up with sound and
picture quality that is often far worse in over-the-counter cassettes than
in recordings he makes at home from his own TV? Thank you. NA
Just time for a postscript on the new releases. Highly commended: Terence
Davies's dazzling elegy to a British childhood The Long Day Closes (Curzon).
Commended: Ghosts Of The Civil Dead (Electric), menacing avant-garde tale of
hi-tech prison life in Australia. Best reissues: Annie Hall (MGM/UA), The
Manchurian Candidate (MGM/UA), Zero De Conduite (Artificial Eye). And
remember: return all copies that are visually or aurally substandard. I do.
*April issue of Sight and Sound, Pounds 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7841 Video Tape Rental.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
