<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Arts: Exhibition with a mission - Lynn MacRitchie shrugs off
a feeling of dismay to applaud the Whitney Biennial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LYNN MACRITCHIE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOOKING at a show like the Whitney Biennial, which opened in New York last
month to howls of protest, is testing for reviewer and gallery goer alike.
After my first visit I came out in despair - so many voices, so many
problems . . .
The Biennial, however, like most large group shows (82 artists are
participating), is best not taken at one gulp. It is the rushed attempt to
form a convenient overview which leads to that feeling of helpless dismay,
the urge to shrug the whole thing off as a gesture by the middle classes to
the dispossessed, or a protest by the blacks or the gays or the feminists or
whoever, got up entirely to make the rest of us, whoever we are, feel bad.
But the show is none of these things. The show is what it is supposed to be,
a selection of contemporary American art, fulfilling the function
established for it by its founder, Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney, nearly 60
years ago. Whitney was an artist herself, a sculptor who produced a fine
series of monumental works, including the memorial to the victims of the
Titanic. When in 1931 the Metropolitan Museum in New York rejected her
offered gift of 400 examples of contemporary America art, she decided to
start her own museum to show them. Being the richest woman in the country
made setting up a museum comparatively easy, but being an artist, committed
to supporting her fellow artists in their struggles and ambitions, made the
function of her museum unique.
This year's Biennial, the first under the directorship of David Ross and
with Elizabeth Sussman as curator in charge, has a mission. The majority of
the artists chosen are engaged with political questions, specifically those
of identity and community. This may be because they have been so throughout
their careers - the wall collage 'Mashe Brusinski' by Nancy Spero on the
subject of the identity of a young Jewish woman executed by the Nazis in
Russia in 1941 comes into this category, for example. Or it may be because
for many artists, such as sculptor Pepon Osorio and many others, making
visible the divers cultures which inform their work has become an accepted
part of the artistic process.
Some have seized the opportunity the Whitney invitation provided to offer a
challenge to an audience they believe to be unaware of the circumstances of
their lives - the entry badges by Daniel Martinez printed with 'I can't
imagine ever wanting to be white' come into this 'couldn't resist it'
category. But in a museum where, its director informed me, a distinguished
guest, standing next to him at the opening, was asked the way to the
bathroom by another guest because he happened to be black, a little 'in your
face'-ness is surely forgiveable.
Other works approach their concerns with subtlety. Of the many installations
in the show, one of the most imaginative is by Maureen Connor who has used
lipstick to make accurate models of the voice boxes of three women. Mounted
on slender stands and lit from above, these eerily beautiful sculptures are
displayed in a curtained area, where the viewer may contemplate their
singularity while listening to tapes of three different women making
wordless sounds.
Sue Williams, who paints about pornography, is not subtle, but she is
powerful, and makes good use of the crude graphic style she shares with
Raymond Pettibon, showing a set of drawings. His exploration of the graphics
of the supermarket and the comic book is evolving into a method of dealing
with the most profound issues (religion is one of the subjects of the
Whitney piece) in the most direct way. This commitment to the use of
'degraded' images or the subject matter of adolescent angst, also
demonstrated by Lari Pittman and Mike Kelley, is evolving into a powerful
statement about American culture, pushing through the trash to the feelings
 -raw, hurting, confused - beneath.
An aspect of the show which may console those worried about the impact of
such unusual forms or practices is the strength of its video section. First
included in the Biennial in 1975, video has become one of the most
satisfying of contemporary art forms. Most beautiful of a strong selection
is the installation 'Tall Ships' by Gary Hill. In this wonderful piece,
viewers enter a darkened space where their movements activate a series of
video projectors each of which shows the image of a different person. As the
viewer moves through the space, a series of ghostly figures advances and
retreats.
Hill's piece, which could only exist in the much maligned age of television,
is beautiful, moving and profound, a tribute to an artist's commitment to a
difficult medium and a rebuke to those who maintain that the new or
experimental can never produce art of emotional content and formal
coherence. Those flickering, wordless figures coming closer and then turning
resolutely away seem to sum up the transitory nature of human encounters and
the profound difficulty of ever really knowing the other - an appropriate
and solemn metaphor for a show which attempts to tackle just those issues.
1993 Biennial Exhibition, Whitney Museum of American Art, 945 Madison
Avenue, New York, until 13 June.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
</IN>
