<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Arts: Primitive times - Salon de Mars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO FEWER than 30,000 Parisians turned up last Tuesday for the opening night
of the fifth annual Salon de Mars art fair, spread out as usual under a
huge, white and badly-ventilated tent near the Eiffel Tower. They were
interested in socialising, not buying, and dealers complained that
collectors were unable to squeeze through the crush to the stands. But
recession, competition from other fairs, slow turnover and a dearth of new
items have all taken their toll this year on a Salon which started out
determined to become a big international event.
This year's Salon, which ends on Monday, has only 92 galleries compared with
115 last year and 120 in 1991. It quite simply lacks a lot of top dealers
who used to come - like pre-Columbian expert Galerie Mermoz and antiquities
dealer, Emmanuel Koutoulakis, of Paris, for example, or ancient Chinese art
specialist, Gisele Croes, from Brussels. None of the really big Paris
furniture dealers is present this year and a dozen stands are manned by
French provincial dealers offering the sort of 18th century furniture, much
of it alarmingly well varnished, which the Parisians do far better.
Five British dealers, however, came over for the fair and were content.
'This is more elegant than Grosvenor House. French buyers take far greater
interest in art than the British, they actually know about it and are
prepared to buy it,' one of them said.
Chinese art specialist Michael Goedhuis sold nearly Pounds 90,000 of art on
the first day to an American and two French collectors. His neighbour,
Robert Hall, from London, is showing tiny 18th and 19th century Chinese
snuff bottles, which have become so popular with collectors over recent
years. Carved in a variety of semi-precious materials, they are priced from
a couple of hundred to over Pounds 10,000 - the most expensive one being in
brilliant white and green jade, which the Chinese call 'pine needles in
snow'.
Martyn Gregory, from London, the world's leading gallery dealing in Chinese
coast paintings - mainly 19th century works by anonymous artists in Canton
for export to the West - is over for its first show in Paris. The art
includes highly-imaginative Chinese portraits of a Spanish and a French
couple of 1760 in gouache at Pounds 4,800 a pair, landscapes and even views
of St Helena and Napoleon on his death-bed, inspired by prints, for Pounds
1,100.
The Salon de Mars originally aimed to give pride of place to contemporary
art, but there are only a handful of dealers this year showing many works
which have been seen before elsewhere. In the field of 19th century
paintings, London's Stoppenbach &amp; Delestre were alone this year with
Barbizon school paintings - one Diaz and five Daubigny landscapes at
FFs120,000-300,000 - and watercolours by Harpignies for FFs35,000-90,000.
Mediaeval statuary is beautifully represented by Boccador and Bresset, from
Paris, and the Salon has two leading dealers in the rarified field of top
Art Deco furniture: Paris's Galerie Vallois has an articulated table by
Printz and two lamps made by Muthesius for an Indian maharajah. The Parisian
gallery, Arc en Seine, has a pair of leather armchairs by Ruhlmann, their
shape inspired by an elephant's head, furniture by Jean-Michel Frank and
alabaster lamps by Chareau, which quickly sold.
It is in primitive art that the Salon de Mars is proving strongest, thanks
to dealers such as Dutko, Ratton et Hourde, Monbrison, Dulon, Deletaille and
Guimiot, from Brussels. The latter is showing 14th and 15th century bronze
objects from the Lower Niger and some outstanding wooden Sepik sculptures
from New Guinea - one, a bird-like flute plug, was held to embody the voice
of an ancestor. Anthony Meyer, whose Left Bank Paris gallery, the only one
in Europe specialising in Oceanic art, brought objects such as a Korvar, the
statue of an ancestor wrapped in a scrap of the latter's shroud, and the
sculpture of a mythological hero by the Yimar people, of New Guinea.
</TEXT>
<XX>
