<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Sport: Where bloodlust rules - Grand National / Michael
Thompson-Noel on the hypocrisy behind a violent horse race
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOW MANY horses will be slaughtered in today's Grand National steeplechase
at Aintree, near Liverpool? One horse, two horses - a trio of hapless
creatures?
In theory, this long-distance slog - 30 fences, 4 1/2 miles, with modern-day
winners taking about nine minutes to complete the course - has been tamed
and made safer for man and beast. In particular, the notorious Becher's
Brook fence has been rendered less barbaric following the carnage in the
1980s.
But the Grand National has not been neutered. In common with all
steeplechase and hurdle racing, it has a dreadful potential for mayhem and
mischief - as witnessed in 1990, the year when Aintree's management was
finally shamed into making significant alterations to Becher's, such as
removing the acute and backwards-facing slope on the landing side of the
fence, and raising the ditch (also on the landing side) by 30 inches.
That year, though, the race still claimed two victims. Scottish Grand
National winner Roll-A-Joint died when breaking his neck at the jump known
as the Canal Turn, and Hungary Hur broke a leg approaching the 19th fence.
The enduring popularity of the National, which attracts a huge TV audience,
is based on its excitement plus betting and bloodlust, although the latter
factor is never admitted. The media love the race. Watch this afternoon's
coverage and marvel at the tortuous lengths to which the BBC goes to cover
up the violence. If you believed its commentators, you would think 40 pit
ponies were hacking round Hyde Park.
Over the years, I have become a connoisseur of attempts by the Grand
National's apologists to present it in a favourable light. A recent example
is Reg Green's introduction to his revised edition of The History of the
Grand National: A Race Apart (Hodder &amp; Stoughton, Pounds 14.99), in which he
calls the race the 'most enthralling of all sporting endeavours.' He goes
on: 'For thrills and drama, the race has no equal on Earth. But, more than
this, it seems to transcend mere sport in its unique power to reflect in one
afternoon the whole of life. Sometimes the tragic, the evil or the cunning
are seen. More often, though, it is the courageous, the humorous, the
generous, the triumphantly optimistic side of life that you will find in the
pages of its history.'
There is a distinct echo here of what Hugh McIlvanney, The Observer's star
sports writer, once claimed. 'The race,' wrote McIlvanney, 'is as arbitrary
and incalculable as life . . . The Grand National is often cruel, but
appreciation of it does not imply sadism or even callousness.' Pull the
other one, McIlvanney.
Even more fatuous was last Sunday's Observer in which Richard Baerlein,
doyen of Britain's racing correspondents, gave the entire game away. 'The
Grand National,' he started, 'is still the greatest betting medium of the
year, and enjoys a worldwide television audience of around 50m.
'But this exposure also brings critics of the race. Armchair viewers, with a
very limited knowledge of the intricacies of racing, protested so strongly
after the deaths of Brown Trix and Seeandem in the 1989 National that the
fences have been trimmed to make jumping less formidable, and the famous
ditch on the other side of Becher's Brook has been filled in.'
What Baerlein did not say was that Brown Trix and Seeandem died in the
grisliest of circumstances. One of them, fatally injured and in danger of
drowning, had to be winched out of the brook at Becher's in order to be shot
by the racecourse vet. What 'knowledge of the intricacies of racing' do you
need in order to write off such carnage as an everyday sporting incident,
let alone as a metaphor for life?
Baerlein did not leave it there, of course. On and on he stumbled. 'The
public,' he wrote, 'have gone 'soft' on their attitude to racing and are
getting softer all the time. If the authorities continue to give way to all
and sundry, in 10 years' time or so they may do away with steeplechasing
altogether, leaving only hurdle racing for the winter. That has already
happened in Australia, and the Americans are leaning that way.'
There is a great deal of patronising snobbery and self-deception in all
this. It is a favourite claim of the jumps crowd that they are a more
fun-loving, down-to-earth bunch than people who merely race horses on the
Flat. The jumps crowd detest being accused of cruelty. And they salve their
consciences by claiming that jumps racing is merely a dangerous sport in the
way that motor racing is dangerous. But racing cars do not smash their
backs, necks and legs, and never have to be shot by the track-side mechanic.
Their self-deception is akin to that of the fox-hunting mob - almost all of
whom are mad - who always claim, with spellbinding arrogance, to be genuine
horse- and country-lovers in touch, at a deeper level than the rest of us,
with Nature and her ways.
Today's Grand National is thought to be wide open. No doubt it will be a
spectacle. But I couldn't care less who wins. For me, the only acceptable
result will be 40 live horses at the start of it and 40 at the end.
</TEXT>
<XX>
