<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Motoring: How to beat the Budget rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STUART MARSHALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOTORING in Britain will cost more: that, in the short term, is the main
effect of last month's Budget. Ten per cent more excise duty on unleaded
petrol and diesel has inflated pump prices by 12p a gallon. The 25 per cent
of car-owners who from choice - or, more rarely, necessity - use leaded
premium are 15p a gallon worse off. And, of course, what some still think of
as the road fund tax also went up by Pounds 15 to Pounds 125.
It could have been worse. Most of the petrol price rise can be clawed back
by more temperate driving habits, such as avoiding high speeds and sharp
acceleration. Bear in mind that a typical family car such as a Rover 214 or
Peugeot 405 uses nearly 20 per cent more fuel at 75 mph (120 kmh) than it
does at 56 mph (90 kmh). A road sign I saw some years ago in Virginia, US,
summed it up neatly: 'Those in favor of saving gasoline, raise their right
foot.'
Petrol in Britain - incidentally, still among Europe's cheapest - will
continue to go up in price by at least 3 per cent a year more than the rate
of inflation. The idea is not simply to raise money. It is all part of a
government strategy to ensure carbon dioxide ('greenhouse gas') levels in
the year 2000 are no worse than they were in 1990.
An immediate and predictable effect will be to boost sales of diesel cars.
Glass's Guide, the car trade's bible, estimates they will climb to 230,000
this year from 200,000 in 1992 (although a gut feeling tells me the figure
could be nearer 250,000).
The once-hefty price premium on diesels, which use up to 30 per cent less
fuel than petrol-engined equivalents, has been narrowed. Surging sales of
diesels have helped. But another reason is that all petrol cars registered
since January 1 have had to have expensive catalytic converters and fuel
injection systems.
Curiously, many cars, including some new ones, still have unnecessarily low
gearing. A 1.8- or two-litre engine spinning at nearly 4,000 rpm at 75 mph
(120 kph) does nothing for motorway fuel economy.
Gearing that is too high can be counter-productive because it leads to
excessive use of the lower ratios. But 25 mph (40 kph) per 1,000 rpm for
family cars under under two litres, and 30 mph (48 kph) for larger-engined
ones, is about right. We ought to be seeing more sensibly-geared cars soon.
Tyres with lower rolling resistance also will help to trim fuel consumption
at moderate speeds. So will improved aerodynamics, althugh there are limits
to what can be done to cut a car's drag if people are still to fit easily
inside.
The eventual casualties of the Budget will be the artificially
small-engined, tax-band beating cars. Some, like the BMW 518i, go
surprisingly well but are not much more economical than larger-engined -
although less income tax-efficient - versions. At 75 mph (120 kph), a BMW
525i uses less petrol than a 518i.
Apart from removing the Inland Revenue's manacles from moderately-priced
diesel cars over two litres cars, the Budget also will make large-engined
but relatively cheap petrol cars more attractive to business users. While
the old tax band rule covering cars under Pounds 19,250 and two litres,
those such as the quick, refined and utterly relaxed 2.8-litre, V6-engined
VW Golf and Vento VR6s made no financial sense. Under the new rules, they
will. So will the Vauxhall Cavalier (Opel Vectra in mainland Europe), which
has just gone on sale with a new, British-made, 2.5-litre, multi-valve V6.
Cars such as these make a simple point; plenty of cylinder capacity in a
fairly small, high-geared vehicle provides big-car performance and driving
pleasure. Light-footed drivers find them moderate drinkers, too.
Will there be a stampede by business drivers to have a pay rise instead of a
company car? The motor trade thinks not.
Many drivers might be better off driving their own cars on a mileage
allowance instead of paying income tax on the benefit of a company Mondeo or
Cavalier. But, in spite of the 8 per cent increase in tax scale charges, a
20 per cent rise in the tax cost of free fuel for private use, and abolition
of the over-18,000 miles a year fuel discount, a company car has three
benefits.
You do not have to borrow thousands of pounds (or lose interest on your own
capital) to buy it. Nor do you need to worry about depreciation, which can
swallow two-thirds of a car's purchase price in three years. Insurance or
maintenance costs are the company's problem, too, not yours.
Some business users have been limiting their tax liability by going for good
second-hand cars instead of new ones. My accountant, a prudent man, has done
so for several years. The trend will develop.
There is plenty of life left in a properly-serviced executive car of
quality. Bought from a franchised dealership under one of many
manufacturer-approved used car schemes, it can be a better bet financially
than a new one.
Saab GB even offers models of its own make up to seven years old, and with
100,000 miles (162,000km) on the clock, in its approved used car programme,
with free 12-month mechanical breakdown insurance thrown in.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
