<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Gardening: Steamy times in a Berkshire jungle - Robin Lane
Fox pulls off the M4 to visit a tropical rain forest and its talented
creator
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBIN LANE FOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WET MIST fell in clouds behind us; simulated thunder rumbled in the
distance; there was an echo of chattering monkeys and I stood on the edge of
Britain's newest rain forest, just north of Newbury, Berkshire, off the M4.
From Wednesday, Wyld Court rain forest will be open to the public: a year
and a half's work, a considerable fortune and the imaginative backing of a
Gold Medal grower of tropical plants make it an experiment which deserves to
succeed. It is bold, lavish and a brainchild: it has something for everyone,
even if piranha fish give you the creeps.
Wyld Court stands in the village of Hampstead Norreys on the former site of
a famous nursery for orchids. Its tropical transformation dates back to a
meeting at Chelsea Flower Show. Since 1985, Barrie Findon has been
delighting the Chelsea public with displays of tropical planting, kept
healthy in a far-from-tropical Main Tent. Two years ago, an appreciative
visitor introduced himself: Keith Bromley, very much the senior citizen,
whose business ventures had left him with funds to invest in a tropical
dream. The Bromley plan was to build a rain forest under glass, put Barrie
in charge, and move in his famous exotics, collected over the past 30 years
and increased by contacts in the tropical world.
In your late 40s, you do not refuse a dream offer. Barrie is now in charge,
with his wife Janet, whom he described inadvertently as his top propagator.
A Dutch system of computers sprays the glass houses with clouds of fine
mist; Barrie has to water all his plants personally and although he has
recorded noises from a natural forest, he would secretly like to add a
visual flash of lightning to the sound of thunder whenever it comes round on
tape.
Wyld Court's aim is to show, preserve and, if necessary, export the flora of
threatened rain forests back to their countries of origin. Many people have
these dreams, but those which prosper are the shared dream of a team. The
plan reminds me of another exotic foundation, Eric Young's trust for orchids
in Jersey: there, the scheme worked so well because it brought together a
backer and an expert cultivator, each of whom needed the other. I sense that
the same is about to happen at Wyld Court.
Give it a few months to settle and then visit it this summer when the huge
leaves are open on the Victoria water lily, the children need amusing and
the giant white Arauana fish by the entrance has grown another two feet. In
nature, it likes to win the high jump: already its practice has broken two
panes of glass in its tank, perhaps because it is being kept up by its
millionaire's diet of chicken breast and smoked bacon.
Personally, I find tropical plants sinister and rather too large for life.
At Wyld Court, the Brazilian passion flower has already grown hugely in less
than a year: its flowers are bigger and brighter than any of those which we
grow on south walls in gardens. Old gardening friends such as the
Clerodendorn turn up with names like splendens and make mine look very
pinched. Rare Daphniphyllums appear with elegant green stripes to their
white colouring, house plants grow to inflated sizes, suggesting that they
would take over the drawing room if mist dripped from the ceiling. Shortly
after my visit, Barrie was booked to receive the reptiles: first, the jungle
snakes, and then, on Monday, the rest of the Press.
Where does it all leave you and me? We will be better informed, no doubt,
about that endless worry, the vanishing rain forest. Whenever one of its old
trees is felled and turned into a cocktail cabinet, tens of thousands of
other living creatures lose a home. Among them are medicinal plants and
hundreds of lovely orchids. Barrie is a great orchid-grower and, at Wyld
Court, he has a golden yellow Catleya which I have never seen before, while
vanderas from Brazil grow on mist and water only without any need for soil.
Beside them, wild orchids dangle from the dry skull of an antelope.
Barrie and his team intend to sell orchids and exotics to visitors along
with what rainforesters call 'dry goods'. The provenance of his collection
makes the nursery an important stop for indoor shoppers, travelling down the
M4.
There is also scope for transplanting Barrie himself. Past clients, he tells
me, have turned conservatories into rain forests for their own amusement.
After long, sweaty years on the Pacific Rim, old dealers retire to the south
coast of England and pine for a hint of the tropics on their bleak,
verandahs. For about Pounds 6,000, Barrie can set them up: he has a client
near Portsmouth who has programmed the mist in his conservatory to coincide
with the evening gin and tonic at 6 pm. The wicker chair might be extra, but
the price includes a full tropical planting, computer controls and setting
by a proven expert, leaving you with Barrie's knowledge, even in his
absence.
Somerset Maugham would have loved it: if you are missing Malaysia, Wyld
Court could convert the conservatory and even, I dare say, find a few
piranhas to remind you of your time in the markets.
</TEXT>
<XX>
