<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Travel: Wheels and deals along the old Silk Road - Marcus
Dalrymple and friends meet the helpful Chinaman, the greedy Chinaman and the
bureaucrat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARCUS DALRYMPLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WE EMERGED from our dingy cabin on to the deck to find that our boat had
reached its destination. To the east, the sun was rising over the grey city.
On the quayside, brawny dockers in grubby white vests were heaving crates on
to a trolley. Paint was peeling off the walls of the custom house in great
flakes. The air was clammy. Hanging limp from a rusty pole was a red flag
emblazoned with the five gold stars of the People's Republic of China.
It was 7am. The four of us had three hours to get ourselves and our bicycles
packed in boxes across Guanzhou to the airport for the next stage of our
journey - a flight to Lanzhou.
Three hours later saw us safely seated aboard China Airways. How we managed
to get there in time is another story, but suffice it to say that in doing
so we encountered three types of Chinaman we were to meet again and again
during our sojourn in Cathay: the helpful Chinaman, the greedy Chinaman and
the bureaucrat.
Lanzhou, the start of our cycle ride, was a large, sprawling and polluted
city straddling the Yellow River. We checked into the Lanzhou Hotel - a huge
grey building that looked like the ministry of defence - and there, over two
days, transformed our four-bedroom area into a bicycle workshop.
By the evening of the second day, and much to the amusement of the cleaning
ladies, we had assembled our bikes and packed our panniers. After a final
visit to the night market for a feast of mutton kebabs, noodle soup and
dumplings, we were ready to go.
The first stage of our 1,500-mile, three-month ride took us 700 miles
north-west through the Hexi corridor. For centuries, this natural passageway
served as the only communication link between Han China to the east and the
land of the barbarians to the west. Bound to the south by the Qilian
mountains and to the north by the Mazong range, great caravans of merchants
travelled at a snail's pace along what later became known as the Silk Road.
With their precious merchandise of silk, spices, gold and armaments, they
crossed thousands of miles of searing desert and snowy mountains exposed not
only to the elements but to marauding bandits. We were fortunate enough not
to encounter any brigands, though both the mountains and the desert
presented us with their own challenges as we followed the age-old trade
route.
From Lanzhou we made good progress, cycling 60 miles a day through the lush
Yellow River delta with its watery paddy fields, picturesque villages and
apple orchards. On the third day our road began to rise away from the river
towards a range of snow-capped mountains.
By 2pm we had begun to climb Maoma Shan, a high pass overlooking arid plains
to the west. For four hours we struggled up the switchbacks, groaning with
the weight of our panniers. Sheep and cattle grazed on the sparse upland
pastures and dotted about the hillside were the flapping sheepskin tents of
herders.
We reached Tianshui that night numb with cold. The town clung to the steep
mountainside like moss to a rock below dark and ominous peaks. We found
lodgings in an old caravanserai just as dusk was falling. Our host, a jolly,
ruddy-cheeked Han Chinese with a mischievous smile, told us that the town
was officially closed to foreigners, but he assured us that we were welcome
anyway.
Reaching Wuwei marked the completion of one stage of our journey. Having
dropped down to sea level from Maoma Shan in an exhilarating and rapid
descent, we found ourselves cycling in quite different country. Ahead of us,
for miles, stretched the long straight road. The desert wind blew
relentlessly with only a few brown hills to block it. Soon our progress was
reduced to 6mph, and by the time we reached Wuwei we were tired, thirsty and
covered in dust.
None of us will have fond memories of Wuwei. Famous for its flying bronze
horse discovered in 1969, it will only ever be remembered by us as the place
where we were spat upon by two old men, where we had a pair of gloves
stolen, and where we bought some buns that tasted and smelt of unadulterated
ammonia.
The small, black dot on our map, 1 inch west of Wuwei, was Yuanshanzi, a
collection of flat-roofed huts surrounded by poplars in the middle of the
desert. We had not intended to stay. We had stopped for a cup of sweet green
tea, with the aim of pressing on to Jiuquan, some 40 miles further on. But
it was a cold overcast day and the tempting offer of a bowl of meat and
noodle soup was too good to refuse.
We stayed for lunch . . . and tea . . . and eventually for supper and the
night, too, since we had been told we could sleep in the outhouse if we
wanted to. Before turning in we took a stroll to the end of the village.
Yuanshanzi enjoys a spectacular location. To the south, just 20 miles away,
the huge, black Qilian mountains, their peaks shrouded in cloud, rise out of
the desert. To the north are the boundless wastes of Mongolia. As the sun
began to set, we stood silently in the sagebrush and watched a steam train
chugging across the vast horizon.
Jiayuguan was the symbolic end to the first stage of our expedition, for it
lies on the very edge of China. For hundreds of years, Jiayuguan's fort, the
last along the Great Wall, defended China to the east against Tartary and
its desert hordes to the west. But like the hoped-for end to so many things,
when we reached Jiayuguan and cycled the short distance out of town to the
castle, we were disappointed.
The overcast sky obscured the view north to the Mazong mountains, a squadron
of soldiers in tatty green fatigues was garrisoned in the tourist car park,
and foreigners were being charged an extortionate fee just to walk inside
the fortress gates for a view of the ramparts.
No doubt, on a clear day, the view of the mountains to the north and south
and of the undulating desert to the west is impressive, but what no
guidebook tells you is that if you turn back east, just a mile away, huge
chemical fertiliser, cement and coke factories stand belching out yellow
smoke into the smoggy sky and the air is filled with the smell of bad eggs.
After refusing to pay the entrance fee, we returned to our hotel
disappointed. As we were locking up our bikes, we were approached by a young
man with a badge on his jacket that read 'China Travel Service.' In English
that was impeccable in all but pronunciation, he said: 'I think you have
just returned from visiting the great fart in the desert.'
</TEXT>
