<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Travel: Stopover sickness - The Practical Traveller
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL, Travel Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EASILY the worst flight I have suffered in years was a recent jaunt from
London to Bali aboard Garuda, the hapless Indonesian state airline, writes
Michael Thompson-Noel, Travel Editor.
First we stopped in Paris. Then we landed in Abu Dhabi. Then Singapore. And
then we changed flights in Jakarta for the last leg to Bali. Total flying
time, from take-off at Gatwick to touch-down in Bali: 23 hours, 25 minutes.
Total travelling time, door-to-door, from Notting Hill in London to the
Grand Hyatt resort, Bali: 27 hours, 45 minutes. The return journey to London
was just as painful. As a result, I had to take to my bed for three days
with systemic collapse. I was not greatly pleased by this carry-on, and
vowed in future always to monitor the travel arrangements made on my behalf.
When I spoke to Garuda, the airline said that at present, because of
international agreements, it was prevented from flying more than three times
per week between the UK and Indonesia, and was in any case not permitted to
fly direct to Bali. From the end of June, however, a new agreement ought to
improve its service to Bali. With luck, it will have two flights a week
between London and Bali, stopping only once, at Abu Dhabi.
There is a clear lesson here - always study the fine print of travel
brochures, and quiz travel agents and airlines closely on the nature of
flights offered. Do not be fobbed off. What you want, wherever possible, is
a non-stop flight. If they tell you it is 'direct', interrogate them
relentlessly to find out what they mean.
Bali is an attractive holiday isle. But you would want to get there
speedily. What is the point of spending thousands on a Bali holiday, only to
see large chunks of time gouged from the start and end of it because of
Garuda's magical mystery tours?
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IDZ  Indonesia, Asia.
</CN>
