London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-16768</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDDAIAEMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930403
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Bed and breakfast
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I HAVE A holding in Jardine Matheson which I am considering 'bed and
breakfasting.' My mother has a similarly-valued holding in North West Water,
for which she is considering doing likewise. Could we avoid the cost of
these deals by swapping the shares via the completion of stock transfer
forms? How would a value then be determined for CGT purposes (in the absence
of contract notes)?
If (as we assume) you are hoping to establish allowable losses, then you
would be frustrated by section 18(3) of the Taxation of Chargeable Gains Act
1992: '(1) This section shall apply where a person acquires an asset and the
person making the disposal is connected with him.'
(3)' . . . If, on the disposal, a loss accrues to the person making the
disposal, it shall not be deductible except from a chargeable gain accruing
to him on some other disposal of an asset to the person acquiring the asset
mentioned in sub-section 1 . . .'
By virtue of section 286 (2&amp;8) of the act, you and your mother are connected
with each other.
The market value of listed shares is (generally speaking) determined on the
quarter-up basis, by virtue of section 272(3) of the act.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
