FT  03 APR 93 / Finance &amp; The Family: Directors' Transactions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By COLIN ROGERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER A quiet period directors appear again to be busy buying shares in
their companies. Selling still outweighs buying, but by a smaller ratio than
has recently been the case.
The largest buy of the week was in Granada Group. Charles Allen, who is in
charge of the leisure division, bought 100,000 shares at 350p, more than
doubling his holding. He and Gerry Robinson, the chief executive, previously
bought stock in the autumn of 1992 at prices between 235p and 247p.
Casket, the bicycles and clothing concern, announced strong interim results
at the end of last year but has not been out-performing the market.
Nevertheless Joe Smith, chief executive, and Ian Butcher, finance director,
purchased a total of 236,825 shares at prices around 33p, increasing their
share holdings sizeably.
In November 1991 directors of ISA International, the information technology
stationery company, bought a large amount of stock at prices between 52p and
64p. Almost 18 months later three directors, including John Heap, deputy
chairman, and Richard Lindley, finance director, have sold approximately the
same amount of stock for 105.5p. Each member of the board still owns a
considerable number of shares.
The Black family still has 30 per cent of Peter Black Holdings, the consumer
product group. The recent sales by Thomas and Gordon Black, the joint
chairmen, of a total of 4,600,000 shares at 170p were made on behalf of
family trusts. At the time of the transactions Gordon Black announced that
the family had no intention of disposing of any more shares in the near
future.
Colin Rogers, Directus Ltd
