<DOCNO>FT932-16775</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDDAIAEFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930403
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Finance &amp; The Family: Time runs out for BES deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOULD-BE tax-shelterers have reached the last chance saloon. Record sums
have flowed into the business expansion scheme this year on the back of
now-outlawed, loan-backed schemes; thus, the end of the tax year is quieter
than usual.
Total investment in the scheme so far this year is almost Pounds 900m,
compared with around Pounds 370m during 1991-92. But there will still be
many people who want to dive into a tax shelter at the last moment.
All the big sponsors, plus the most important intermediaries such as the
Allenbridge Group (071-409 1111) and BESt Investment (071-936 2037) will be
open during the weekend for those who have left it late.
Anthony Yadgaroff, of Allenbridge, estimates that the very last moment for
investing will be 5.55 pm on Monday when it would still be possible to fax
applications to a sponsor, or deliver them to a locally-designated
solicitor.
Deals over five years are now more generous than they were while loan-backs
were on offer, and there is plenty of interest in schemes which underwrite a
certain uplift and then allow the possibility of extra 'upside' if the
residential housing market performs better than expected.
But the best advice at the end of the tax year, as ever, is to play safe
and, if in doubt, do nothing at all. It is still possible to invest another
Pounds 40,000 by the end of December, and those who do not use up their BES
allowance this year can carry back some relief from the next tax year.
Enterprise zone trusts have operated over the past few years as a twin
market to the BES. This year, however, they are more like poor cousins. Very
little property is on the market, and this appears not to be selling
quickly.
EZ investment is as tax-efficient as the BES, with the added virtues that
there is no maximum annual limit and tax relief is available on loans taken
out to fund EZ investment.
But the underlying investment, commercial property, is much less flexible
because it, too, is afflicted by terrible market conditions.
Ian Pugh, of Allenbridge, points out that the yields available on EZ trusts
are running at around 7 per cent while commercial yields outside zones are
around 10.
Given that enterprise zones are unlikely to be in desirable areas, the
premium paid for tax relief is hard to justify. So, for the moment, there is
little case for a hasty EZ investment,
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6799 Investors, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT932-16776</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DDDAIAEEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930403
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Finance &amp; The Family: The Week Ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
TESCO, the UK's second-largest grocery retailer, will be hoping to reassure
the City with a healthy rise in full-year profits on Tuesday. Its shares
have been under pressure on the stock market amid fears that its sales
growth is lagging behind that of rivals J Sainsbury and Argyll, owners of
Safeway. Most forecasts are clustered around the Pounds 580m mark, compared
with Pounds 545m last year, although some are as high as Pounds 585m.
Full year figures on Monday for 1992 from MB-Caradon, the building products
and security printing group, are expected in the region of Pounds 120m to
Pounds 125m, against Pounds 106.4m in 1991. Lower interest charges and a
solid performance from the managed businesses are behind the expected rise.
The main point of interest is how the group will reinvest the Pounds 473m
proceeds of the sale of its 25.3 per cent stake in CarnaudMetalbox,
announced last Friday.
TIP Europe, the trailer rental company, is expected to announce
disappointing interim results on Tuesday. The company's Mobiel subsidiary,
which supplies temporary buildings in continental Europe, is understood to
have run into management and planning problems.
Analysts have downgraded forecast full year forecasts from Pounds 8.8m to
Pounds 6m while interim profits are likely to be about Pounds 2.4m from
Pounds 3m last time. The dividend is also in danger of being cut for the
third year running.
Sun Alliance Group, the composite insurer, is expected on Thursday to report
a loss for 1992 of around Pounds 150m, a recovery from a loss of Pounds 466m
a year earlier. However, it is likely to maintain the dividend.
Mirror Group Newspapers, buffeted by board room upheavals including the
recent departure of Lord Hollick, is forecast to produce on Monday pre-tax
profits of between Pounds 27m and Pounds 33m (Pounds 47.3m) for 1992.
Any comments by the management on editorial direction will be closely
scrutinised, particularly by the Labour party, which is worried that the
Daily Mirror might drift to the right politically.
First-half pre-tax profits on Monday from Highland Distilleries, maker of
Famous Grouse scotch whisky, will be boosted by the company's decision to
equity account its 35.4 per cent stake in Robertson &amp; Baxter, the whisky
blender. However, analysts expect the underlying pre-tax figure to reflect
pressures on volume sales and prices of new and mature whisky. Forecasts
suggest the outcome will be between Pounds 13.5m and Pounds 14m, 5 per cent
to 8 per cent below last year's Pounds 14.7m.
</TEXT>
