<HEADLINE>
FT  03 APR 93 / Finance &amp; The Family: Guarantees - are they worthless? /
Scheherazade Daneshkhu looks at building society 'promises'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN the Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester building society launched its Best 90
account in February, it gave a guarantee that it would pay the highest
90-day rate of any of the top 10 societies or Abbey National. The guarantee
lasts until at least May 1994.
But since none of them has yet taken up the challenge, C&amp;G has not had to
change the rates offered on Best 90's four tiers, ranging from 7.5 per cent
gross to 8.55 per cent.
Despite the lack of challenge, at least investors have a guarantee that is
worth something. In the building society deposit market, the word
'guarantee' appears to be, in too many cases, either worthless or
meaningless.
'Guaranteed differentials became fashionable in 1990 when the building
societies started to launch variable bonds,' says Christine Bayliss, of
Moneyfacts. 'Depending on what account they are linked to, they may be good
or not worth much.'
Many guarantees, for example, promise to pay a certain amount above the rate
for a selected account (chosen usually because the account does not pay a
competitive rate in the first place).
Alliance &amp; Leicester's tax-exempt special savings account pledges to pay 4
per cent above the society's ordinary gross share rate, now 0.5 per cent.
The society admits the latter is 'just about the lowest rate of interest you
can get on any account.'
The rate on the Tessa itself is 7.25 per cent, or 6.75 percentage points
above the ordinary share rate. Competitive pressure means that rates have to
be considerably higher than the guaranteed differential, effectively
rendering the guarantee meaningless.
Abbey National's first-issue Tessa also had a guaranteed differential, but
for a greater amount - 5.5 per cent - above the bank's Instant Saver
account, now paying 0.5 per cent gross.
Just when this was looking as if it might become useful, Abbey launched a
second-issue Tessa which pays 6.3 per cent on its lowest tier. Abbey has
abandoned the guarantee.
Woolwich launched a two-year investment bond in December which also
guaranteed to pay 'at least 4 per cent' above the society's ordinary share
rate of 1 per cent gross. The bond is tiered and its lowest rate is 7.5 per
cent gross.
So what is the point of the guarantee? 'It simply means that, whatever
happens, the rate will always be what we promise. It is a safety net,' says
the Woolwich.
Similarly, Bradford &amp; Bingley's two-year bond, launched last month, offers a
guaranteed 4.5 per cent gross differential over the rate on its basic
Timesaver savings account, which pays 0.5 per cent gross. Interest paid on
the minimum tier, starting with a Pounds 5,000 deposit is 7.25 per cent
gross.
Some accounts promise to hold a rate until a certain date. Yorkshire
building society today is launching a postal account paying competitive
rates of interest. The society guarantees to hold these until July 1.
Northern Rock's Go Direct postal rates were guaranteed to April 1 when the
account was re-launched at the beginning of January with 8.05 per cent gross
on the Pounds 2,000-Pounds 10,000 band. It was closed to new customers on
February 10.
'After the subsequent base rate cut and rumours of more to come, it was
reassuring to know that these rates would stay,' says Bayliss. 'However, if
the account was still open, people would still need to be mindful that these
rates were issued before the last base rate cut and could, therefore, be in
line for a sharp drop at the end of the guarantee period.'
Unfortunately, some guarantees are only as secure as the company that
provides them. Investors with Birmingham Capital Trust's 12 per cent
fixed-rate Tessa were transferred to a lower rate with another provider when
the loss-making account was closed at the end of last year.
</TEXT>
